<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / UK Company News: On course against the odds - US purchase
became a black hole / Logica
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Can Logica recover the panache which in the early 1980s made it the UK's
most buccaneering and stylish computing services company? Or is it condemned
to further restructuring, decline and eventual acquisition?
The company remains a maze of contradictions. Highly visible, oozing with
technological expertise and with the bluest of blue chip customer lists, it
has nevertheless been a financial stretcher case more than once during its
25 year existence.
The shares at 292p on Friday are where they were a decade ago. In the year
to June 30 1993, the company made pre-tax profits of only Pounds 9m on sales
of over Pounds 217m.
Logica was a leader in some superficial aspects of corporate culture when it
pioneered annual reports which were masterpieces of good design. However,
few companies have so relentlessly underperformed both the market and their
sector.
Mr Richard Holway, a computer industry authority, describes it as a missed
UK opportunity: 'It is Britain's largest indigenously owned computing
services company, yet it is not even in the European top 50'. The
appointment of Mr Martin Read as chief executive a year ago may mark the
beginning of the long journey back.
As the UK's last large independent computing service company, Logica has
been a perennial acquisition target - most notably in 1985 when a
parliamentary furore helped prevent a swoop by Electronic Data Systems of
the US.
Some would argue that Mr Read's appointment is proving tantamount to a
takeover given the radical changes he is trying to make.
Formerly with GEC-Marconi where he had responsibility for businesses with
sales of Pounds 500m, he is injecting a cool measure of market realism into
Logica's technological hot-house culture.
He has begun to put his own people into key positions: Mr Jim Yates,
recruited from GEC, has direct responsibility for the company's poorly
performing international businesses, while Mr Jim McKenna has been brought
in as human resource director, a key role in transforming the corporate
cul-ture.
The problem, in part at least, is that within Logica, founded by engineers,
technology has always come first with sales and marketing dragging along at
the rear. 'We have lacked punch, focus and an international, market-led
culture', Mr Read explains.
The company's lack of competitiveness over the past five years was
exacerbated by the worldwide recession, by the retirement of co-founder
Philip Hughes, the company's style guru. But most of all Logica was hit by
the problems of Data Architects, a US-based banking and telecommunications
software company which it bought in 1988, hoping it would provide a platform
for US expansion.
It became, instead, a financial black hole for the company, pulling down
profitability and leading to successive waves of restructuring in the US.
Now the problem seems to be nearly solved although the US subsidiary is
still losing money because of the continuing cash needs of developing a
funds transfer package.
How do Logica's management regard the purchase of Data Architects now? Mr
Colin Rowland, currently director of international operations, believes on
balance it was 'a great mistake'. Mr Yates, however, argues that an
international services company has to have a base in the US to provide a
pathway into a broad range of opportunities.
Mr Read's strategy at Logica is based on two elements. First, a drive to
improve margins and profitability. He plans to build on the company's
existing technical excellence and the loyalty of its customers. He is also
anxious to instil 'rewards-led' rather than 'technologically' driven
attitudes.
The aim is to achieve a return to at least a 10 per cent return on sales;
between 1988 and 1992, operating margins fell from 10.2 per cent to 3.1 per
cent followed by a return to 4.1 per cent in 1993.
Second, a renewed search for repeatable sales, leveraging the company's
international network to find new markets for products and services that
have proved successful in the UK. Some 50 per cent of the company's turnover
comes from the UK; Europe accounts for 28 per cent, North America, 12 per
cent and the rest of the world, 10 per cent.
Mr Read has a lot to do, however, to sharpen the company's focus. About a
third of its business is in the finance sector while the rest is spread
between government, energy and utilities, defence, telecommunications,
transport and industry.
About half the business is in fixed price contracts, the rest being charged
on a time and materials basis.
Mr Read and his senior executives talk of the company as being 'liberated'
from the layers of bureaucracy which, they say, built up over the past
decade, stifling initiative and drive.
'Mobility' is another watchword. He is working towards a flat, flexible
corporate structure which will enable highly skilled and mobile
technologists to move anywhere their services are needed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
