<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Lipton appeal setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The struggle by Mr Stuart Lipton, chief executive of Stanhope, to block a
deal in which British Land acquired a 29.9 per cent share of Stanhope has
suffered a further setback in the Court of Appeal.
In a unanimous decision the Court of Appeal dismissed an application by Mr
Lipton's private company for leave to appeal against an earlier court ruling
striking out proceedings by his company against British Land and the Bank of
Nova Scotia.
Mr Lipton had claimed pre-emption rights over the 29.9 per cent stake which
British Land acquired from the Bank of Nova Scotia in March.
However, his case was dismissed by Mr Justice Vinelott earlier last month.
The judge refused leave to appeal and costs were awarded to the defendants.
On Friday in the Court of Appeal Lord Justice Millett upheld that ruling
describing the case as 'speculative' and adding that the plaintive's
allegations were 'wildly implausible'.
Mr Lipton had been anxious to overturn British Land's acquisition of the
stake, which is seen as a step to gain control of Stanhope's half-share in
Broadgate, a development in the City of London.
He said he had the right of first refusal to buy the stake.
</TEXT>
