<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Bulls run upagainst realists in bleak Japan: Why companies
are much more pessimistic than the markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For months the world's fund managers have been selling Japan to their
clients. In a world haunted by rising inflation and interest rates, Japan,
they say, offers growth potential. For the past two weeks, the corporate
reporting season has put the sales pitch to the test.
The hard facts of the 1993-94 results offered little more than the bleak
superlatives of decline: a record fourth successive year of falling earnings
pushed corporate profitability to depths last seen in the early 1970s;
pre-tax profit margins as a percentage of sales fell below 2 per cent, down
from a postwar high of nearly 6 per cent in 1989. Overall, turnover fell by
5.4 per cent and pre-tax earnings by 16.2 per cent.
Manufacturers were worst hit. Their aggregate profits dropped by a fifth.
But it has been an undiscriminating recession; other sectors fared only
marginally better. The culprits were familiar: weak demand at home and a
surging yen abroad.
And yet for the moment it seems the equity market believes not only that the
worst is over, but that Japan's companies are actually set for years of
rapid growth. While the rest of the world's stock markets have taken to
heart the principle of selling in May and going away, the Nikkei greeted the
results season with a sustained rally, building on its steady rise since the
start of the year. It now stands 21 per cent above its year-end level. The
earnings collapse and equity price surge have sent price-earnings ratios
back to their bubble highs.
The bullish justification is that things can only get better. The company
results, though poor, actually beat market expectations, or as Mr Jason
James, equity strategist at James Capel, puts it: 'The results were better
than expected, because it was always possible that they would be
disastrous.'
Just a month before the reporting season, analysts were forecasting an
average 23 per cent fall in pre-tax profits. By that yardstick, a 16 per
cent fall is encouraging.
But while results were better than expected, companies' own expectations for
the current year have turned out to be worse than market forecasts. Most
observers had been expecting a rebound of more than 16 per cent in 1994-95
earnings. But the annual reports projected an aggregate improvement of just
9 per cent. For the first time companies are much more pessimistic than the
market.
Some see this as an encouraging sign. 'Japanese companies are at last having
a dose of realism,' says Mr Jesper Koll of SG Warburg. 'They are no longer
relying on either an economic or a policy bail-out to keep them afloat, but
are instead looking to real improvements in their own performance.'
If real improvements are to be found in 1994, they are likely to come in
three areas.
Demand: While many companies reported improving conditions in overseas
markets, particularly Asia and the US, there was little optimism about
domestic demand. Their average forecast is for another fall in sales, of
around 0.2 per cent, as real demand weakness is exacerbated by price falls.
The yen: Exporters were caught out by the appreciation of the yen in
1993-94. Last year on average they expected a rate of Y115-Y120 to the
dollar. The actual figure was nearer Y105. This year most major exporters
are playing safe and basing their earnings forecast on an exchange rate of
Y105. This assumption may prove conservative and offers some hope for
improving profits.
Many companies have taken out protection against the currency's gyrations by
shifting production offshore. According to Mr Robert Burghart, strategist at
Smith New Court, the most striking feature of the 1993-94 results was a
direct correlation between earnings and the scale of the company's offshore
production. The electronics sector led the way, with companies such as Aiwa
seeing higher profits as a result of an aggressive reorganisation of
manufacturing operations.
This reorientation is reflected in forecasts: manufacturers are much more
optimistic for the current year than other sectors, expecting pre-tax
profits to rise by 18 per cent, while non-manufacturers expect a fall of 4
per cent.
Costs: 'Restructuring' has been the vogue word throughout the recession. The
1993-94 results suggest that companies have indeed trimmed costs to keep
afloat. Employee bonuses, on average 30 per cent of total employment costs,
have fallen by about 4 per cent this year. Headquarters costs have been held
back for a third successive year.
Exemplar of the trend was Ricoh, the photocopier manufacturer, which was one
of the few companies to post higher profits, despite falling sales, thanks
largely to the disposal of unprofitable divisions and better control of
other costs.
But such measures have not yet yielded results for most companies. There is
little hard evidence that deep, structural cost-cutting, as distinct from
cyclical shrinkage, is widespread. Payroll numbers have fallen only slightly
and the commitment to lifetime employment, a significant contributor to
companies' long-run costs, remains mostly undiminished.
It is possible that companies' relative pessimism about the current year
will prove excessive. The yen may fall and domestic demand may turn out
stronger than expected. But if their expectations prove well-founded,
earnings growth will be sluggish at best, and they will rely on their own
internal reforms for recovery. Only those businesses for whom restructuring
is a reality rather than an aspiration will justify the market's optimism.
Japanese results, Page 22
</TEXT>
<XX>
