<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / IBM aims to unify software development in 'Workplace'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International Business Machines is realigning its worldwide software
development operations following a management review ordered by Mr Lou
Gerstner, chairman and chief executive.
IBM, which spends about Dollars 1bn a year developing software in several
product divisions, plans to co-ordinate these efforts behind a set of
technologies called 'Workplace'. The shift is part of Mr Gerstner's plans to
unify IBM's product development work, eliminating contention between
divisions.
Workplace technologies are designed to create a common core for IBM's
computer operating systems. Similarly, the company has fixed on a common
hardware technology, the PowerPC microprocessor, for a broad range of
products ranging from hand-held units computers to powerful multi-processor
units.
The software strategy shift will achieve several goals, according to a memo
sent to senior IBM managers by Mr John Thompson, senior vice president, who
headed a taskforce formed by Mr Gerstner to evaluate Workplaces
technologies. The aims include shortening software development cycles and
cutting costs.
Mr Thompson said the new technologies would enable IBM software products to
work together better in distributed computing systems. This addresses one of
the 'strategic imperatives' established by Mr Gerstner to increase IBM's
share of the fast-growing market for computers linked to networks.
During the overhaul, Mr Thompson stressed that the company aimed to enhance,
rather than replace, its existing software. 'Our customers' investments (in
software) will be protected,' he said.
Market quest, Page 21
