<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Costs soar in battle for Lasmo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE and PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Enterprise Oil is expected today to extend its hostile Pounds 1.3bn bid for
rival explorer Lasmo as the costs of the battle between Britain's two
largest independents spiral to more than Pounds 30m.
By the time the offer period expires at the end of July, Lasmo will have
spent Pounds 20m-Pounds 25m defending its independence. Enterprise is likely
to pay a similar price in fees and charges if successful and a mere Pounds
5m if the bid fails. Combining the two companies could cost Enterprise more
than Pounds 80m in restructuring charges, although advisers say overhead
savings of Pounds 30-Pounds 40m a year could be achieved.
The offer is likely to be extended to June 17, with most investors expecting
the all-paper bid to be revised. A new offer could include some form of cash
or a revised paper deal in the light of Enterprise's weakened share price.
As the battle nears the half-way stage, Lasmo is set to question further
Enterprise's accounting standards, but it is also expected to retract an
earlier charge that Enterprise has had little international success. It did
not include Enterprise's Norwegian operations in its calculations. It has
been invited to give the Takeover Panel additional details of allegation
that Enterprise's techniques allowed it to inflate earnings.
Lasmo will come under pressure to persuade institutional investors that it
has the financial resources to exploit all its development opportunities.
One shareholder said price was not the main issue. Lasmo needed to show that
it was a better developer of assets than Enterprise. 'Lasmo has to prove to
us that it deserves its independence.'
Although Enterprise has come under attack for not fully explaining the logic
behind its offer, speculation intensified that the bid had been motivated in
part by the chance to swap some of Lasmo's assets.
'There is a bit too much confidence on Enterprise's part for them not to
have done deals or know they can do them,' said one institutional investor.
A combined company would have the largest acreage in the UK continental
shelf. Asset trading would strengthen cash flow and the combined balance
sheet, allowing the larger group to accelerate appraisal and development of
Lasmo assets in Algeria and Colombia.
The bid values Lasmo paper at about 130p, compared with Friday's 148p close.
Jewel in the crown, Page 19
