<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / UK may stem imports of subsidised building steel: Companies
unable to compete with foreign rivals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Regulations to stem imports into Britain of cut-price subsidised
construction steel, mainly from Italy and Spain, are being considered by the
UK government.
Transport and Environment Department officials are working with the British
Constructional Steelwork Association to devise quality control and company
registration schemes to make it harder for foreign companies to break into
the UK. The standards will be similar to schemes operating in other European
countries and will be carefully worded so as not to fall foul of European
Union trade liberalisation rules.
Companies including British Steel have become increasingly irritated that
foreign rivals find it easy to win work in the UK while, they claim, many
continental European markets remain heavily regulated. They are particularly
concerned at a sharp rise in the number of UK bridge contracts awarded to
Italian and Spanish companies. They claim that they use cheap subsidised
steel produced in their own countries to undercut competitors.
There were strong protests by British companies and MPs 19 months ago when
Cimolai, an Italian steelwork fabricator, won a Pounds 7m contract to supply
steelwork for the Pounds 300m new river Severn crossing.
The BCSA estimates that Pounds 30m of work, representing roughly half of all
steel road bridge contracts, has been placed with Italian or Spanish
contractors during the past 12 months.
The largest is a 3,600-tonne contract to cross the A406 Angel Road in north
London, awarded to Ensidesa, a Spanish steelwork contractor. Wimpey, the UK
construction group, is the main contractor for the road contract.
BIT of Italy recently won a 1,600-tonne contract for a crossing of the A417
Brockworth bypass near Gloucester for which Amec is main contractor.
Main contractors say they are working for little or no profit margin and
have no choice but to accept the lowest price from steelwork subcontractors.
Initiatives being pursued by the UK government include a quality assurance
scheme requiring British and foreign companies to be certified by a
recognised body that they can meet standards drawn up by the transport
department.
The Department of the Environment is proposing a registration scheme
requiring companies to meet financial, environmental, technical and health
and safety standards before being allowed on tender lists.
Environment officials say construction companies operating in Spain must be
registered before they can do business. Italy also requires companies to
register for various categories of public works.
Japan's steelmakers under pressure, Page 22
</TEXT>
