<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Second arrest in Schneider inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Belgian investigation into Mr Didier Pineau-Valencienne, chairman of
France's Groupe Schneider, broadened with the announcement yesterday of the
arrest of an Italian businessmen as part of a fraud inquiry involving
Belgian subsidiaries of the electrical engineering company.
Belgian justice officials said yesterday that Mr Valentino Foti had been
detained on the same charges as Mr Pineau-Valencienne. The Schneider
chairman, held in Brussels since his arrest on Friday, is charged with fraud
and falsification of accounts. This follows an investigation triggered by
complaints from minority shareholders in Cofibel and Cofimines, two Belgian
subsidiaries of the French company.
Mr Foti, 60, appears to be linked to the investigation through his role in
PB Finance, a shell company which used to have interests in mining. He was
the majority shareholder in PB Finance, in which Schneider held a minority
stake through Cofibel.
Groupe Schneider sold its stake in PB Finance earlier this year and has
firmly denied reports in the Belgian press which claim the company may have
been involved in money-laundering.
Mr Pineau-Valencienne and Mr Foti both presented themselves voluntarily in
Brussels to make statements concerning an investigation into the management
of Schneider's Belgian subsidiaries.
They are both due to appear in court tomorrow when a decision will be taken
on whether to prolong their custody.
Industry observers in Paris played down the impact of the events on
Schneider.
'The Belgian companies represent only 5 per cent of the Schneider group
assets which would suggest that the financial effect of these complaints
will not threaten the group as a whole,' said one market analyst. Shares in
the company, which fell by 5.6 per cent on Friday following the announcement
of Mr Pineau-Valencienne's arrest, rose yesterday by FFr10 to FFr400.
French businessmen and the media have reacted with dismay to Mr
Pineau-Valencienne's arrest. French prime minister Edouard Balladur
telephoned his Belgian counterpart, Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene, at the weekend to
discuss the issue.
</TEXT>
