<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / The Lex Column: Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
With the benefit of hindsight, it is clear that two long-term trends
supported the equity market in the 1980s. The steady rise in dividend payout
ratios, recently highlighted by the government, helped support share
valuations. The steady drift of UK pension funds out of bonds and into
equities underpinned liquidity. Whether or not the government moves to
reverse the first trend, pension funds may start to drift back in favour of
bonds.
At the start of the 1980s, the average scheme belonging to the National
Association of Pension Funds had 2.5 active members for every pensioner. By
the end of last year, that ratio had fallen to almost one to one. Industrial
restructuring and the wave of early retirements doubtless accelerated this
process. While there is no reason to expect a further sudden shift in the
balance, the assets of many pension funds are already a poor match for their
liabilities.
Exactly what proportion of funds' liabilities now relate to pensions in
payment is difficult to judge. For the average scheme, though, the figure is
likely to be around one third. While such liabilities would normally be
matched by investing in bonds, pension funds have on average only 11 per
cent of assets held in fixed-interest and index-linked bonds. Large
surpluses built up during the 1980s allowed trustees to ignore the problem.
But with surpluses falling - the reduction in gross funds' tax credit on
dividends contributed to the erosion - the mismatch of assets and
liabilities is more difficult to defend.
</TEXT>
