<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / The Lex Column: Germany
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Financial markets were expecting US interest rates to rise this year, even
if they responded badly when they did. They were less inclined to factor in
the more optimistic economic mood in Germany. Helped by rising export
orders, it now looks as though the first quarter's gross domestic product
figures could show surprisingly robust growth. Bond and equity markets must
soon learn to cope without the prop of falling official rates. Indeed, they
may start to wonder when rates will rise again.
When the Bundesbank was operating a restrictive policy, its basic concern
was inflation and it tended to remain unmoved by economic slowdown.
Optimists argue that, conversely, it will now be less worried about economic
recovery as long as inflation continues to fall. On that basis, the easing
could have some way further to go. But inflation is now below 3 per cent and
the fall may decelerate. It is hard for the Bundesbank to justify lower
interest rates while money supply continues to exceed its target by such a
wide margin. At 4.5 per cent, the discount rate is already close to its 4
per cent trough in 1983. It looks unlikely to revisit the 2.5 per cent low
of 1988, which in any case held for only six months.
In the short run, this looks more of a problem for the bond market. Yields
on 10-year paper, which historically tend to average around 4.3 points over
the inflation rate, already assume inflation well below 3 per cent. Factor
in the poor international climate and it is difficult to see why they should
fall back again.
Equities at least have the economic recovery to consider. Earnings should
reap the double benefit of corporate restructuring and increased demand. But
much of this was already reflected in last year's 50 per cent rise. Even the
equity market is likely to flag if high long-term interest rates prove a
drag on the recovery next year, when tax increases will also sap consumer
demand. It would then be scant consolation if weak demand for credit made
the Bundesbank as slow to raise rates as it was to bring them down.
</TEXT>
<XX>
