<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Leading Article: Too soon to rule alone
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Hungary's Socialist party won an absolute majority in the second round of
the general elections over the weekend. But it will probably do a service to
itself and to the country if it rejects the temptation to go ahead alone.
Instead, the Socialists should seek to attract the Free Democrats into a
broader-based coalition government, even though the price of such a
government would be the sacrifice of the prime ministerial ambitions of Mr
Gyula Horn, the veteran former communist who led his Socialist party to
victory. Despite the fact that voters have given the Socialist party a
powerful vote of confidence, many Hungarians will question the legitimacy of
one-party rule by politicians with roots in the communist past.
There are also doubts whether the party alone would be able to keep to the
difficult path of market-based reform, given the strength of support shown
by the election for traditional socialist policies. Higher social spending,
greater job security, a slowdown in privatisation, and higher taxes on the
emergent business class are the sort of policies which many of the party's
former communist voters and its powerful trade union wing are likely to
demand from a one-party Socialist government.
Such pressures would be diluted if the party, at its extraordinary congress
this coming weekend, demonstrates that it is indeed a reforming, modernising
force in Hungarian political life. It could do this best by endorsing the
market-orientated reform line associated with Mr Laszlo Bekesi, the party's
finance minister.
The most convincing endorsement would be to chose Mr Bekesi himself as the
party's prime ministerial candidate. This would please the Free Democrats
and open the way for a coalition which would be the best guarantee of
reforms needed to reduce the current account and budget deficits, and
continue the modernising process begun by the outgoing Hungarian Democratic
Forum.
Main obstacle
The main obstacle to such an outcome appears to be the understandable
ambition of Mr Horn, who gives every indication of wanting to lead the next
government.
He is undoubtedly a tough and skilled politician and a survivor. As foreign
minister in the last communist government Mr Horn executed the decision to
open Hungary's western borders to East Germans in 1989. This act fatally
undermined the government of the late Mr Erich Honecker and led to the
domino-like collapse of communist governments throughout the region,
including Hungary's own reform-communist regime led by Mr Miklos Nemeth.
Old regime
For that act alone Mr Horn is warmly regarded by many in the west,
especially in Germany, with which he has already indicated a desire for the
closest possible relations once the new government is formed.
But for millions of Hungarians Mr Horn remains a man of the old regime, a
participant in the suppression which followed the Budapest rising of 1956.
His leadership could open up barely healed scars and would be watched
apprehensively by the international community. Foreign investors, who hold
Dollars 25bn of Hungarian debt and have invested Dollars 7bn over the last
four years in what has been perceived as a stable, pro-market reforming
country, would focus a particularly close eye on such a government.
In Poland, under similar circumstances, the victorious Democratic Left led
by Mr Alexander Kwasniewski offered the premiership to the Peasants party as
the price of bringing its junior partner into a coalition. Hungarian
Socialists on the reformist wing of the party in particular will argue at
this weekend's congress that the party must make similar concessions to
bring in the Free Democrats, who made clear before the second round of
voting that they would not serve in a coalition headed by Mr Horn.
Now the Free Democrats' position is weaker because the electorate has given
the Socialists the power to rule alone if need be. Paradoxically, however,
the Socialists probably need the Free Democrats more than ever. A coalition
provides the best way for the Socialists to convert their return to power
into good government for Hungary, and longer-term rehabilitation for a party
which has sole power in its grasp too early for its own good.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>HUZ  Hungary, East Europe.
</CN>
