<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Observer: A tale of two companies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
What would Sir John Swire, the president of his family's Far Eastern trading
house, or Sir Ron Brierley, the corporate predator, make of the Ocean Group
today? Both men know the company well. Sir John sat on the board for several
years and Sir Ron once made a bid for the company.
Ocean used to pride itself on the breadth of its management, picking its
chief executive from a band of 'crown princes' groomed for succession. The
late Sir John Nicholson was one, as was Sir Lindsay Alexander. However,
Ocean is down to its last 'crown prince'. After 30 years with the company,
chief executive Nicholas Barber, 53, has handed in his notice and
headhunters are trawling for a successor.
Warning lights start flashing when a sizeable company cannot find its own
chief executive from within. But then Ocean today is a scarcely recognisable
descendant of the Liverpool shipping company formed nearly 130 years ago by
Alfred Holt with the help of another local merchant, John Swire.
There was a time when you could not visit a Far Eastern port without
spotting one of Ocean's Blue Funnel liners and Swire's early growth in the
Far East owes much to Holt's support. But by the 1960s the two companies,
whilst retaining close links, were going their separate ways. Ocean went
public and has been struggling to adapt ever since. Its vulnerability was
obvious to an outsider like Sir Ron Brierley, who made a Pounds 300m bid in
the late 1980s. He lost because City institutions felt Ocean's management
should be given more time to transform the business.
Meanwhile, Swire has prospered as a very private UK family business, albeit
with stakes in two big public companies, Cathay Pacific and Swire Pacific.
Its success in the Far East proves that the decline of an old family
business need not be inevitable.
The next chief executive of Ocean, on the other hand, may have a tough task
proving to the institutions that Ocean still deserves their support if
another Ron Brierley turns up on its share register.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Ocean Group.
</CO>
