<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Still warning and encouraging: On the eve of his 90th
birthday, Warburg's Henry Grunfeld gives Ian Hargreaves his views on today's
financial world
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Henry Grunfeld plans to celebrate his 90th birthday tomorrow with a day off.
That will, indeed, make it something special; there have not been many
working days off for Grunfeld in the 60 years since he fled from Hitler's
Germany and teamed up with Siegmund Warburg to create what has become
London's leading investment bank, SG Warburg.
Today he works, a portrait of Siegmund over his right shoulder, in a plain
corner of Warburg's offices in the City. At one end of the building,
razor-headed young traders punch keyboards and grab phones. Around Grunfeld,
an oracular stillness sits.
Warburg announced last week that Grunfeld will surrender his position as
president of the bank next year, but he has no plans to change his routine:
weekdays in the office, evenings at home in Belgravia, weekends in his
Surrey country home, talking, reading and listening to music. 'I still come
in each day because I enjoy it, because it's healthy and because I can make
a contribution,' he says. That contribution he sums up in Bagehot's phrase
about constitutional monarchs, 'to advise, to encourage and to warn'.
The years have not decreased the flow of subjects about which he feels
inclined to warn. Whether discussing the 'absolute menace' of hedge funds,
Wall Street-style bonuses or the risky financial edifices of derivatives,
Grunfeld is forthright.
Hedge funds he denounces as anarchic and speculative vehicles. 'I've nothing
against Mr (George) Soros personally; I don't know him, he appears on TV and
makes a nice impression. But if Mr Soros and his hedge fund can effectively
force us to leave the European exchange rate mechanism, there must be
something wrong,' he says. The hedge fund technique reminds him, he says, of
an earlier generation of British stock pushers. 'They would buy quietly a
great number of shares and then make it known that they were buying, so lots
of people follow and the price goes up. That's the philosophy of hedge
funds.'
He discounts the idea, however, that regulators can or should act against
such funds, arguing that 'if there are a few more losses, they will regulate
themselves'. More serious, he suggests, are the increasingly large and
exposed trading positions of many commercial and investment banks. 'That is
quite rightly a worry of the central bankers and the regulators. In America,
we have the situation where banks which have federal deposit insurance are
holding large trading positions. The New York Stock Exchange actually
delayed the opening of trading in Bankers Trust until the bank had made a
statement about rumours of heavy losses. This is an extraordinary event
which has not been sufficiently highlighted.'
The spread of derivatives - complex financial instruments based upon future
commitments to buy, sell or swap financial assets - has, Grunfeld believes,
only compounded the problem by giving traders and their employers a false
sense of security. 'A lot of this business is pure speculation,' he says,
although he thinks that a recent spate of problems with derivatives
contracts involving the likes of Procter &amp; Gamble, Metallgesellschaft, Arco
and Dell Computer will cool the over-enthusiasm. 'If more and more customers
are losing money, then the volume will go down.'
For the banks, he says the key is 'complete separation of traders and
accountants', given the long tail of risk that derivatives contracts can
drag behind them. Warburg, he acknowledges, has joined the scramble to amass
derivatives expertise, which plays a crucial part in the design of many
deals for customers, but he argues that Warburg has spent the necessary time
training its accountants and displayed prudence in proprietary trading.
'It's all a question of volume. It is not a question of whether Warburg does
these things, it's a question of how much we are doing.'
As for fat bonuses and remuneration packages, Grunfeld says that years of
watching Warburg salaries dragged skywards by American competitors has not
altered his underlying view that pay systems have lost touch with reality.
'We can't help it', he says of Warburg's own pay levels, recalling a debate
with an American member of the firm about a rumoured Dollars 6m-a-year
contract at a rival bank. 'Why shouldn't a man earn Dollars 6m if he makes
Dollars 50m for his employer?' came the question. 'I say, 'but what if he
loses?' ' says Grunfeld. 'Why, then he is sacked,' says the American. 'That
is the great difference between us,' says Grunfeld. 'If someone here makes a
mistake, we don't sack him, we try to help him so that it doesn't happen
again.'
Grunfeld couples this earnest and unfashionable paternalism with passionate
advocacy of a more patient approach to banking, based upon building
relationships with clients and countries, rather than fighting an endless
succession of contests for the next transaction, based chiefly upon price.
Asked what Warburg has to learn from its competitors, especially the big
American houses it trails in the battle for the so-called 'bulge bracket' of
top business-getters, Grunfeld snorts: 'I wouldn't like us to learn the
pushy and ruthless way that some of the American houses try to get
business.'
Asked about Warburg's strategic priorities, however, he names only one: to
become a more effective global player, with an ever more effective network.
'The global aspect of the financial services industry is something that will
last,' he says, unlike the latest fad in leveraged buy-outs, or emerging
markets. 'I like the New York definition of emerging markets,' he adds,
'that an emerging market is one where, when there is an emergency, they
don't pay.'
He sees the biggest competitive resistance to Warburg on the continent
coming not from the American houses, but from the continental universal
banks, whose tight links with local business are used to harry foreign
investment banks from their turf. 'To me, it is incomprehensible that these
banks should be creditors, shareholders and members of the supervisory board
of their customers,' he says. 'The power these banks have is far ahead of
the American banks.'
Behind all these comments lies half a century of culture-building inside
Warburg. Grunfeld acknowledges that cultural change has been inevitable as
numbers have increased from the dozens he once supervised to the 5,500 who
work for the bank across the world today. But the relatively
non-hierarchical structure of the bank, designed to encourage teamwork and
keep stars happy, is something Grunfeld works hard to maintain. He recalls a
recent conversation with a director in his mid-30s looking for guidance
about the next decade of his career. Grunfeld's advice: 'If you stay here,
you must feel that what you say is being taken into account, that the head
of your department only runs the department, but not you. I believe he left
my room with a happier face.'
Managing large numbers of high-powered, opinionated and ambitious
individuals is of the essence in investment banking. With the announcement
last week that Sir David Scholey is also to step down next year as the
bank's chairman, Warburg faces a shift of generation in its leadership. What
are the qualities the new bosses will need? 'The first thing is a strong
personality,' Grunfeld says. 'As the business has developed, no chairman can
know everything, but he needs to want to be a leader.'
The last time Grunfeld was interviewed by the FT, in 1987, he commented
famously that 'hiring people is similar to buying a tie. You don't buy the
tie when you need one. You buy the tie when you see one and like it.'
Although he still believes in his own instinct for spotting talent, he says
the days when Warburg would spontaneously hire bright journalists or
diplomats in the belief that knowledge of banking could come later are
probably gone.
He retains his faith, however, in one of the bank's better-known recruitment
eccentricities, its use of graphology. In the 1920s, he was working in the
family steel business in Germany and petty cash started to go missing. There
were three suspects, all of whom had worked for the company for more than 15
years. Grunfeld was persuaded to seek the advice of a handwriting expert,
who immediately identified the culprit. Confronted by Grunfeld, the employee
confessed. 'We didn't dismiss him and he never did it again,' he says.
Grunfeld maintains to this day that graphology will reveal flaws in
personality and even health, such as proneness to depression. 'There is not
one case in 60 years where the graphologist has said something that turns
out to be wrong,' he says. 'The practice is regarded as odd in Britain, but
it's widespread in Germany, Switzerland and France.'
He thinks it not altogether untypical of his adopted homeland to discount
the wisdom and experience of foreigners, even, he notes, while being driven
by them from most sections of manufacturing industry. 'Somehow we haven't
woken up to the end of empire,' he says. 'All those jokes about frogs may be
very funny, but it doesn't help. Frenchmen are to be taken seriously. All I
can do is to educate.'
One wonders whether Grunfeld, with his self-discipline and his principles,
would have been attracted to banking if he were now in his 20s rather than
his late 80s. 'Oh yes,' he replies, without hesitation: 'It's the only
business I can think of where you have every 30 minutes a new problem or a
new situation. In industry, it's more or less the same every day.'
He is equally certain that Siegmund Warburg would have wanted none of it.
'He would have accepted the need for the changes, but he wouldn't have liked
it.' His co-founder's genius, he says, was 'that he had ideas. He was really
two or three persons in one. He was a very good banker, but he never wanted
to be a banker, he wanted to be a teacher in a university. He was interested
in many things, in people and politics, as well as having a great knowledge
of banking.'
He admits to not liking the recent account of the Warburg family story, by
the American writer Ron Chernow. 'My real objection is that he leaves you
with the impression that you would rather not have liked to know Siegmund
Warburg. As Goethe said: 'Where there is a lot of light there is a lot of
shade.' That applies to human beings. Siegmund Warburg was an outstanding
person, with a superb instinct.'
How would Grunfeld himself like to be remembered? There is a pause, then a
comment about the formative years of the bank in which Grunfeld became a
confidant of many senior British industrialists. 'I was like a doctor to
them and that's why there will be no memoir. I will leave this world without
telling anybody,' he says. Then another pause. 'So far as my role in the
firm goes, well someone here said it the other day in three words. 'You ran
it.' Well, I did.'
The interview over, Grunfeld shuffles to the door. As we disappear down the
corridor, he's tapping at the monitor outside his office, muttering: 'Now,
what's going on in the stock market?'
