<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: UK's 'silent industrial majority'
must show support for Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Lord CHALFONT and Others
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, British industry must stand up and be counted in the forthcoming
European election.
There are four key issues which we, as chairmen and chief executives of
leading industrial and business organisations, support and regard as vital
if Britain is to play its full part in Europe, as well as creating jobs and
wealth:
1) We support the development of a single market on the assumption that
Europe remains able to compete successfully in a global marketplace and does
not become 'Fortress Europe'.
2) We believe it is inappropriate to speculate on the formation of a central
bank or a single European currency until it is much clearer how and when the
economic convergence of European states, which vary significantly in
economic and political terms, will be achieved.
3) We believe the full implementation of European employment legislation
would severely damage the competitiveness of British industry in world
markets and increase levels of unemployment. While recognising the
responsibilities of industry to its employees, the British government must
continue to resist the implementation of such legislation as European works
councils and restrictions on working practices.
4) We wholeheartedly support the continuing government commitment to the
geographical expansion of the European Union.
The silent industrial majority must make its voice heard above the political
bickering.
Lord Chalfont, Sir David Alliance, Sir Peter Cazalet, Sir Colin Chandler,
Michael Doherty, Sir Barry Duxbury, Dick Evans, Eugene Fife, Rocco Forte,
Jon Foulds, Jeffrey Herbert, Roger Holland, David Hubbard, Michael Jackaman,
Martin Jourdan, Leonard Kingshott, Sir David Lees, Sir Christopher Lewinton,
George Magan, John Nelson, Sir David Plastow, Alastair Ross Goobey, Andrew
Seth, Christopher Sharples, Sir Allen Sheppard, George Simpson, Cob Stenham,
William Wells
</TEXT>
