<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / The dye is cast by growth and costs: European chemicals
companies are shifting bulk capacity to Asia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS and EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The dragon shifted one way, then the other, as it advanced on the Scotsman.
The creature twisted, contorting to the sounds of drums and cymbals, the din
momentarily overwhelmed by the spatter of fireworks.
Then there was silence. Sir Denys Henderson, chairman of the UK's top
chemicals company, Imperial Chemical Industries, stepped forward. The dragon
had warded off the evil spirits that could have jeopardised his company's
latest venture: a plant, capable of making 350,000 tonnes a year of pure
terephthalic acid, a plastic used mostly in bottles. Sir Denys could now
open the Pounds 150m factory in Kuan Yin, Taiwan, with confidence.
The ritual was a far cry from ICI's traditional manufacturing centre in the
bleak landscape of the River Tees in the north-east of England. The ceremony
some months ago heralded a trend in the European chemicals industry as it
refines its global strategy, shifting bulk chemicals capacity from the
industrial centres of Europe to the rapidly expanding economies of Asia.
Sir Denys is not the only European chairman opening plants in Asia. His
counterparts from Swiss, German, French and other UK chemicals groups have
been investing in locations as diverse as India in the west, Vietnam in the
east, China in the north and Jakarta in the south. If successful, the
migration could ensure the long-term survival of the European companies. But
it raises serious questions about Europe's prospects as a manufacturing
base.
The reason for the reorientation is Asia's rapid economic growth, explains
Mr Ronnie Hampel, ICI chief executive. The buoyancy of the region's
economies is having a knock-on effect on the Asian chemicals market which,
excluding Japan, grew 8 per cent in 1993, according to BASF, the German
group. Such heady progress contrasts with a European chemicals market which
recorded zero growth last year. By the end of the decade, the Asian
chemicals market, including Japan, will be worth Dollars 500bn a year -
about the same as the European or the US market, forecasts BASF.
This expansion is being fuelled by the shift of entire sectors to low-cost
south-east Asian countries. 'The area enjoys high growth rates in textiles,
electronics, and automotive engineering, all of which are significant
customers of the chemicals industry,' says Dr Manfred Schneider, chief
executive of Bayer.
A further factor is that Asian chemicals groups will become serious
competitors to the Europeans in the next decade. By shifting production to
Asia, the Europeans hope to compete effectively. 'A combination of lower
costs and modern technology will enable them (the Asian countries) to become
exporters to other parts of the world. Asia's share of world exports of
organic dyestuffs grew between 1982 and 1991 - just one decade - from 13 per
cent to almost 24 per cent,' says Dr Schneider.
Dr Hans-Helge Stechl, BASF board director responsible for Asia, says the
company is building a dyestuffs plant in Shanghai that will export to the US
and Europe. The group is also constructing a dye plant in Mangalore, western
India.
Sales growth in south-east Asia has been rapid. Ciba, the Swiss group, has
benefited from double-digit growth in turnover in the Asia-Pacific for the
past three years. In 1993, more than 16 per cent of group turnover was
generated in the region. The company plans to increase that proportion to 20
per cent by the late 1990s. Similarly, Bayer's turnover in the Asia-Pacific
area has increased by more than 30 per cent since 1990, and reached DM5.58bn
last year, 14 per cent of group sales.
Capital investment has followed sales. 'At an early stage we realised it
would only be possible to share in the dynamic growth of the market by
committing ourselves to local production,' says Dr Stechl. The company had
invested DM1.2bn in Asia before 1993, but has a further DM1.8bn committed to
new projects in south-east Asia, excluding Japan. It presently invests
between 8 per cent and 10 per cent of its capital spending in the region, a
figure that is expected to rise to between 15 per cent and 20 per cent over
the next few years, according to Dr Stechl.
For ICI, capital for investment over the past three years has been in short
supply. But Asia remains a priority, says Mr Hampel. Last year, the company
spent more on capital projects in the Asia-Pacific than in the UK,
continental Europe or the US.
Most European investment is being put into the fast-growing Chinese market,
which could be worth as much as Dollars 100bn by the year 2000, the same
size as Germany. BASF, which has five joint ventures in China, hopes to have
sales of DM1bn by the end of the decade. Ciba of Switzerland has also set
China as its priority in the region and has invested Dollars 200m there.
One country not benefiting from investment into Asia is Japan. Apart from a
plant to make replacements for ozone-depleting CFCs used in refrigeration
and air-conditioning, opened by ICI this year, little European money is
being invested by chemicals companies in the region's largest economy. This
is partly because of the recession. But the strong yen, high manufacturing
costs, and the migration of the electronics and automotive industries to
low-cost centres elsewhere in Asia, have also contributed.
While European chemicals companies are being lured to the rest of Asia, at
the same time they are being driven away from their home bases by high costs
and what manufacturers perceive as an ever-tightening regulatory
stranglehold.
Dr Schneider warns: 'The main disadvantages we have to face are higher
labour costs and expensive social security systems, coupled with widespread
regulation of environmental affairs by the state. We have to overcome these
handicaps. If we do not, many areas of our business (in Europe) will become
uncompetitive and therefore in danger of being squeezed out of the market.'
Dr Stechl agrees. 'High costs in the established countries are forcing
producers to take evasive action, moving to countries where labour and
capital expenditure costs offer a more favourable economic framework.'
Labour costs in Taiwan are 21 per cent of those in western Germany; those in
Singapore and Hong Kong are 20 and 16 per cent respectively, according to
Bayer.
The consequences of this evasive action are clear. Last year, for the third
year running, capital investment by the chemicals industry in Europe fell,
down 14.3 per cent. Employment continues to decline: since 1990, the number
of jobs in the sector has fallen by 160,000, according to the European
Chemical Industry Council, which predicts a further drop of 60,000 this
year. The prospects for Europe as a manufacturing centre for bulk chemicals
is grim.
While Asia offers the chance to escape from the low-growth lethargic markets
of Europe, industry leaders warn that significant profits could prove
elusive in the short-term. The reality of doing business is challenging,
says Sir Denys. Industrial relations, taxation and foreign exchange problems
all pose difficulties, he says. Some companies have had to pull out.
Hoechst, for example, withdrew from its foray into South Korea - a joint
venture with Lucky Goldstar - because of lack of profitability.
'Anyone who thinks the streets of Asia are paved with gold needs to have his
illusions shattered. It's bloody hard work,' Sir Denys adds. It looks as if
ICI will be using the services of dragons for some time to come.
Additional reporting by Emiko Terazono
