<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Arts: Sunny side up with Roger Ackling - Visual arts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM PACKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is conceptual art and conceptual art. The fatuities of what we have
come to call it in its limited sense are only those of its exclusive and
self-conscious avant-garde extreme.
Yet all art, and all true craft too, must have something of the mind, of
sentience and intention to them, some informing idea, at least at the
outset, or the activity and engagement are nothing more than mindless
occupational therapy. Pace Saint John, all things were made by it, that is
to say the idea, and without it was not any thing made that was made. The
artist declares his initial interest and method, the patron his requirement:
the rest is a matter of emphasis.
It is only when that informing idea alone is taken as the justification of
the work, and the form left unconsidered to shift for itself, that
conceptualism becomes limited, pretentious and self-serving. For the rest,
we can only wait upon results as they come, to take on their merits, for
better or worse. So it is that within the scope of conceptualism in its
broader sense, these 30 years past, we have had isms and attitudes that have
produced work of real and lasting quality and interest, for all that it has
come sailing in under the Jolly Roger of the experimental, the radical and
avant-garde. Minimalism, for example, with its reduction to the simplest
physical presence or statement; systems art, in which form is the function
of process and the application of a set of rules; nature art or arte povera,
of which the point is to celebrate and exploit the qualities of found and
natural objects and materials.
Roger Ackling, whose largest show in this country in number of works
exhibited is filling the Annely Juda Gallery, contrives in his quiet and
self-effacing way to engage fruitfully with all these conceptual isms at
once. His Flooded Margins of his title are, in this instance, the beaches
and foreshores of East Anglia, from which he takes the driftwood fragments
that are his tabulae rasae. Only a pair of wretched, derelict plimsolls here
seems out-of-place. His principal tool is the burning glass, which makes him
entirely dependent upon the sun, just so long as it shines. He works where
he is, while the moment lasts, the rules which he accepts - as opposed to
imposes upon himself  - the arbitrary ones of weather and sunshine and
whatever the object is that chance throws in his way.
But that is not to say that the work itself is arbitrary or automatic, left
to run on of itself. Rules and process may together determine its nature and
appearance in the general sense - just as a painting may be a thing of paint
on canvas - but its singularity lies in what the artist alone makes of it.
And Ackling's creative signature is unmistakable. He moves the glass
laterally across the surface of the wood, the scorched line steady and set
at regular intervals. But even here, innate and intuitive differences and
decisions reveal themselves.
The wood itself is hard or soft, to be worked in its appropriate way. It is
washed clean perhaps, or perhaps dense with a surface history of old paint,
rusty nails, vestigial hinges, and all to be taken into account. The
compositions are thus as various as the objects themselves, subtle and
responsive, for all that Ackling's approach is insistent in its formality -
frontal, architectural, hieratic. The horizontal bands set up a moire shift
against residual streaks of old paint or tar on a weathered disc: a pristine
shadow is left within the linear system by the removal of the protective
skin of old metal: the scorched diptych holds attention upon the clean,
sharp gap between its component panels: surfaces are disrupted, systems
interrupted, contradicted.
But in spite of all such explanation and special pleading, all this order
and process, all this conceptualising, what we end up with is a set of odd
and ambiguous objects, beautifully made under the artist's own hand, and
each one just as he thought it might be, not at the moment he started, but
when he left off. None of them are exactly big, many of them tiny. They are
what they are, no more, no less, rich in the associations and references we
may care to bring to them, but that is entirely up to us. These things are
like fetishes and talismen, perhaps, trophies of long-forgotten rituals and
special moments, half-remembered.
For the artist himself such memories are naturally more particular, but then
he alone knows the place where he picked up his trophy, and how he felt
about it, and how warm the sun was as he marked it for his own. And he is
artist enough, romantic and imaginative, to keep his counsel. The boring,
portentous conceptualist would hardly resist spelling out the message.
Ackling, for his part, is saying nothing, and good for him.
Roger Ackling - Flooded Margins: Annely Juda Fine Art, 23 Dering Street W1,
until June 25.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
