<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Business and the Law: Rolls-Royce defeated by shareholders -
Legal briefs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
An attempt by Rolls-Royce to buy out the listed preference shareholders in
one of its member companies, Northern Engineering Industries, against their
will, has been defeated in the Court of Appeal.
Rolls bought Northern in 1989. In January last year it called an EGM to
authorise a reduction of its share capital by repaying and cancelling its
preference shares. Rolls, as the holder of all ordinary shares, passed the
resolutions. Commercial Union, which held some preference shares through a
nominee, objected.
The Appeal Court upheld that objection. It said the attempt to buy out the
preference shareholders was not in accordance with their rights. The case
hinged on Northern's articles of association, which entitled preference
shareholders to a separate class meeting to approve any 'reduction in
capital'. Northern argued that repaying the whole of the paid-up capital on
the preference shares was not a 'reduction'. The court disagreed.
Mr Edward Walker-Arnott, senior partner of City solicitors Herbert Smith,
said the case had established 'an important point of principle for all
institutional shareholders'. Many listed companies have articles protecting
preference shareholders' rights.
</TEXT>
