<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Management (The Growing Business): Keep family and firm
together - A feud among relatives is especially harmful when they own a
business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALDEN LANK and MONICA WAGEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Once a family that owns a business gets down to serious feuding, both the
familial ties and the company are at risk. One remedy is to set up a 'family
council' - a practice which has been adopted by some continental European
companies. Its aim is to reach consensus on difficult issues.
The family and the company are two disparate systems. The family invokes the
idea of stability, caring, co-operation and fidelity; the company focuses on
change, evaluation, competition and efficiency.
Family proprietors have to find ways to minimise the inevitable and
dangerous conflicts between the business and the family - or face the risk
of a commercially damaging argument. An effective family council comprises
chosen members of the owning family that meet regularly to discuss concerns
of the family as a family as well as the family business.
The council provides a forum that can discuss issues such as: what do we
stand for as a family?; what is our responsibility to each other and to the
outside world?; and what is the family's role in relation to the business?
The council should encourage shareholders, heirs, spouses and other family
members to talk to each other, enabling them to anticipate problems, such as
a lack of liquid assets or succession, and to seek equitable solutions.
The very existence of a council also serves the purpose of reminding
employees of the family's continued interest in and concerns for the
enterprise.
A family council that shares anecdotes about, say, the founder or episodes
in the company history keeps alive and refines the traditions that the
family - and the business - value. The council can pass these to the next
generation, while instilling a sense of responsibility towards company and
community.
Family council meetings are appropriate for discussing philanthropical
objectives, contributions to cultural schemes, improving the company's image
by sponsoring social activities, and so on.
It can inculcate among family members the notion that the privilege of
ownership brings financial advantages but also generates responsibilities.
A family council is one of the best ways to help the business family to
explore what ties them together - and that helps to prevent conflicts that
could harm the company. The council can also develop a family spirit that
encourages consensus as well as effective and constructive communication.
The tricky issue of transferring ownership and management to the next
generation is probably the most significant factor in the demise of family
companies. It is important that the ambitions of children, expectations of
the retiring generation, the option to sell or merge and the repurchasing of
shares, to name a few debating points, are considered and studied freely by
the council.
Precise rules - such as age, education, training and experience - should be
laid down and observed when family members take certain jobs in the company.
Conditions for promotion, transfer and leaving should be made explicit. The
selection process of a new chief executive officer, whether or not a member
of the family, may also be eased by discussion in the il.
Many family company boards of directors exist to rubber stamp decisions or
to take an advisory role. Such arrangements suit certain companies, but at
some point the composition of the board can make the difference between
success and failure.
The effectiveness of boards whose membership only reflects various interest
groups in the family can be seriously hampered. Family councils can be an
excellent forum for determining the ideal number and qualifications of board
members, family or non-family, thus increasing the board's professionalism
and effectiveness. Some families use their council for choosing who
represents the family on the board.
Resistance to forming a family council tends to come from those who have
power and responsibility in the company. They do not like sharing
information because they fear criticism and loss of authority. But these
concerns can be allayed by keeping to some rules.
A family council should not be used for solving problems directly linked to
management of the company. Day-to-day operation of the business is not a
suitable subject for debate by the council. This means drawing clear lines
between the family and the company that are understood by family members and
top management.
A family council must not intrude on the functions of the board or of the
general management, but should keep to its distinct role - defining and
preserving certain family values, both as a family and as owners of the
business.
It is particularly unfortunate if a family council is exploited for
influencing or even manipulating certain members of the family to gain
advantage in purely personal matters. The council is effective only if the
common interests and the objectives of such meetings have been clearly
stated - perhaps in a document - a kind of constitution or mission for the
family.
This would set out the values and aims that the family adheres to and the
way they should be expressed towards the company and the community. It would
be the basis for fixing objectives and practical strategies, and for
steering a joint effort.
Family councils are not a cure-all and must be tailored for each family and
its business. What they do offer is a formal way of getting relatives to
talk to each other usefully and make better business decisions.
Alden Lank is Stephan Schmidheiny Professor of Family Enterprises and Monica
Wagen is Research Associate at IMD International in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</TEXT>
<XX>
