<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Management (The Growing Business): Permission to proceed -
Local planning officials can be potential allies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Next month South Tyneside councillors in the north of England will try to
resolve a nine-year planning wrangle.
They will consider an application by Mayflower Glass, a local company that
has twice won the Queen's Award for Export for its decorative glassware, for
retrospective planning permission for its storage warehouse and ancillary
buildings, part of a former Ministry of Defence depot on green belt land
bought in 1985.
Mayflower Glass says the controversy has left it in limbo. Its expansion
plans are blocked, and 100 jobs are threatened should it be forced to vacate
the warehouse and use part of its nearby factory, outside the green belt,
for storage.
The problem, which has already caused two public inquiries, is a headache
for the company and the council. But, says Jed Griffiths, president elect of
the Royal Town Planning Institute, time-consuming dogfights can be avoided
if businesses treat the planners as potential allies.
'I see planning as a positive force, maintaining a balance between local
interests, environmental concerns and the need to regenerate the economy,'
he says. This, he admits, is not how many businesspeople view it. 'There is
still a lot of suspicion and mistrust of planners.'
Griffiths, formerly chief strategic planner with East Sussex County Council,
concedes some planners may be too 'finicky'. But he believes current changes
in the planning regime in England, described by the Department of the
Environment as a move to a 'plan-led system', should make it easier for
companies to understand the planning context in which they are operating and
avoid pitfalls.
By 1996, all local planning authorities must have in place district-wide
local plans, looking at least five years ahead. 'The new system puts the
development plan at the centre of things - it's the framework,' says
Griffiths.
Many of these plans, called Unitary Development Plans in metropolitan areas,
are currently undergoing public consultation. Companies should take an
interest, says Griffiths, as this could affect what they will be able to do
at their existing premises.
For those seeking sites, now or in the future, his motto is simple: be
positive and consult the planning authorities first. At the very least, this
can save wasted time in fruitless applications. And, with local authorities
increasingly active in economic development, companies may find a warmer
welcome than they expected.
Important information arising from these discussions is worth getting in
writing, just in case. 'Too many conversations take place in the rugby
club,' observes Griffiths.
Nor should companies forget that the democratic process involves councillors
as well as planners. Kenneth and Jill Wheeler, who run a pet crematorium
near Langley Park, County Durham, discovered this to their cost when they
decided to combine an expansion of their small business with an improvement
of their facilities to meet new environmental legislation.
Derwentside district planners recommended the go-ahead for the Wheelers'
plans: the councillors, lobbied by locals worried about the issue of
incineration, rejected the application. The Wheelers won their case at a
public inquiry, but it cost them anxiety, wasted time and Pounds 20,000 in
solicitors' and consultants' fees.
In the case of Mayflower Glass, a proposed modification in the currently
very restrictive national green belt guidelines may come to the rescue.
The government has proposed that the re-use of existing, redundant buildings
in the green belt should not be refused without 'specific and convincing'
reasons, a change intended to tackle the problem of sites like MoD depots
and psychiatric hospitals.
A final decision on this modification is expected in the autumn but
Griffiths' basic dictum still holds true. 'Land use planning is all about
being in the right place.'
</TEXT>
