<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / The Hualon Project: Grounds for delay -
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JENNY LUESBY AND GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OCTOBER 1990
The Irish Republic announces a deal with Hualon to set up a IPounds 45m
textile plant at Gillogue in Limerick.
MARCH 1991
After visiting Taiwan, Mr Des O'Malley, the Republic's industry and commerce
minister, cancels the project, following allegations of stock fraud by two
of the three brothers who run Hualon.
APRIL 1991
Oung Ta-ming, who heads the Hualon group, and Oung You-ming, chairman of its
textiles division, are charged with breach of trust in a stock scandal that
brings down a Taiwanese cabinet minister.
SEPTEMBER 1991
Oung Ta-ming and Oung Yi-ming, chairman of another Hualon division, are
charged in Taiwan over irregular land deals.
1992
Talks open between Hualon and Northern Ireland, and re-open between Hualon
and the Republic, on the possibilities for an aided textile plant.
OCTOBER 1992
Oung Ta-ming convicted on stock scandal charges, which are upheld on appeal
to the high court. He appeals against a 2 1/2 -year sentence to the supreme
court. Oung You-ming had already jumped bail to Malaysia. Oung Yi-ming's
conviction on land deal charges is quashed.
1993
The Republic again backs away from the Limerick project, this time because
it believes it is not economically viable.
The British government agrees to back a proposal by Hualon for a Pounds 157m
textile plant near Belfast with Pounds 61m aid.
JULY 1993
The European Commission announces an investigation into the legality of the
aid package.
MAY 1994
The commission clears the aid, in spite of expert objections that a market
does not exist for Hualon's products and that it would not increase net
employment.
JUNE 1994
Contract due to be signed.
</TEXT>
