<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / College faces cuts after union deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department for Education is expected to cut funding for a Manchester
further education college which has offered lecturers new contracts limiting
teaching time.
Any such move by ministers would be a further escalation of the dispute
between the Natfhe lecturers' union and college principals. The dispute
started in April last year when colleges were removed from local authority
control.
On Saturday the union used its annual conference to announce an agreement
with the Manchester College of Art and Technology. This places a limit of
756 hours on each lecturer's teaching time a year and gives contractual
safeguards on the length of the working week.
In February Mr Tim Boswell, the further-education minister, said that up to
Pounds 50m would be withheld from colleges' budgets unless they removed
'restrictive practices'. The money would be released only 'when there had
been satisfactory progress within colleges towards more flexible contracts
of employment'.
However, lecturers plan to strike in 120 colleges next month, aiming for
contracts similar to Manchester's.
The union yesterday inducted a new president, Ms Doreen Cameron, while Mr
John Akker, the union's next general secretary, pledged that the union's
tactics would not change.
Mr Roger Ward, chief executive of the Colleges' Employers' Forum, which
negotiates on behalf of most principals, said the Manchester contract was
'largely irrelevant' because 332 colleges were already implementing new
contracts in line with the government guidelines.
</TEXT>
