<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Evidence on costs fails to stem outsourcing growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Businesses are contracting out their data processing operations at an
unprecedented rate in spite of growing evidence that many deals prove
unsatisfactory and more expensive than in-house operations.
The sharp rise in outsourcing - or facilities management - was the principal
reason for an average 11 per cent rise in revenues among British computing
services companies last year, about twice the rate of the previous year and
a faster growth rate than elsewhere in Europe.
The Holway Report, an annual analysis of the financial performance of UK
computing services companies which is being published this week, says
outsourcing revenues of the main computing services companies grew 25 per
cent in 1992 and 33 per cent last year to Pounds 665m.
The report says the value of new contracts awarded last year exceeded Pounds
3bn, equivalent to Pounds 400m a year. It says the value of the market will
grow by at least 40 per cent in 1995. By 1997 the UK outsourcing market is
likely to be worth more than Pounds 2bn annually.
Companies are turning to outsourcing for a variety of reasons, but mainly to
do with cutting the cost of data processing. Typically, a business sells its
data-processing operations to a computing services company which undertakes
to provide an agreed level of service for a fee.
Anecdotal evidence that outsourcing does not always bring the anticipated
benefits is given credence by a survey of 160 large European companies. This
shows that poor preparation and inadequately drafted contracts were common
and a frequent cause of disputes.
One respondent said: 'The contract did not have strong enough performance
measures. I think they took advantage of us and I do not blame them. We were
not very professional.' Another said: 'The contract was too loose; every
time we sneezed it cost us Pounds 10,000.'
Mr Kevin Tomlinson of CMS, a British Steel outsourcing subsidiary, said:
'Outsourcing contracts are agreed in concept and delivered in detail and
that is why they break down.'
The survey, by Business Intelligence, a London-based consultancy, says the
companies most likely to experience difficulties were those which approached
outsourcing as a solution to a problem 'without adequate consideration of
the wider implications'.
The result, it warns, can be loss of control of critical IT resources,
disruption to the organisation and a cost far in excess of retaining data
processing in-house.
1994 Holway Report. Richard Holway, 18 Great Austins, Farnham, Surrey, GU9
8JQ. Pounds 1,450.
Outsourcing IT. Business Intelligence, Forum House, 1 Graham Road, London,
SW19 3SW. Pounds 395.
</TEXT>
