<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / North-west sees patchy recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The largest companies in north-west England are struggling out of recession,
but with a performance that is far from uniformly good, according to an
analysis of local companies.
The analysis, aggregating the results of the 127 quoted companies reporting
to the London Stock Exchange and those of private ones filed with Companies
House, shows lacklustre results from the region's two conurbations - Greater
Manchester and Merseyside - but strong contributions from Lancashire, the
Potteries and Cumbria.
The research, by accountancy firm KPMG and Insider, a regional business
magazine, has been published as North West England plc in the style of an
annual report.
Mr Alan Benzie, head of KPMG corporate finance in the north-west, says in
the report that the financial sector was the strongest in the last year,
with leisure and media industries also doing well. There were 'creditable
performances' in electricals, retailing and textiles.
However the food sector was flat while chemicals, industrials, property and
construction all struggled.
Aggregate turnover rose 5.5 per cent but operating profits were only 1.5 per
cent up. Cheaper money saw interest paid fall 8.7 per cent.
Recovery was confirmed by improved investment in fixed assets, a 10 per cent
increase in depreciation provision, and an increase in stocks of 4.3 per
cent, reversing the de-stocking trend of the recession.
Jobs continued to be shed with a 1.9 per cent fall in numbers employed.
Total pay rose 4.7 per cent, well ahead of an inflation rate of about 3 per
cent.
'Fragility and patchiness' is one of the principal messages of North West
plc. Mr Benzie says flickering trading conditions are improving slowly but
there is some way to go before there is a 'sustainable glow'  - and national
and international factors, not the north-west's own efforts, will be
decisive.
Trafford Park, the Greater Manchester industrial estate, appears to have
reversed the decades of decline that prompted the government to put it under
an urban development corporation in 1987.
A census of companies in the park shows a net increase of 126 since 1991,
bringing the total to 1,314. New businesses accounted for 360. The rest were
relocations.
North West England plc. Newsco Publications, Mindel House, Minshull Street,
Manchester M1 3EF. Pounds 35.
</TEXT>
