<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Blunkett backs work scheme to curb crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A citizens' volunteer service to encourage thousands of school-leavers to
spend three months on community projects was backed yesterday by Labour's
Commission on Social Justice.
Most of the cost of a national Citizens' Service with places for up to
150,000 young people would be offset by a reduction in crime and an increase
in the employability of young people, the commission says in a report to be
announced today.
The scheme would cost less than Pounds 2,000 per person including a weekly
allowance of Pounds 50 for the volunteers.
Mr James McCormick, a research fellow for the commission and author of the
report, says: 'Improved employment prospects and reduced crime rates would
pay back the investment. By its fifth year every Pounds 100 invested in a
service covering 150,000 young people could yield savings of up to Pounds
25.'
The scheme should not become a public works programme or be a means of
substituting for paid labour, says the commission, a think-tank set up by
the late John Smith at the end of 1992 to advise on social policy.
Instead the scheme would bridge the gap between education and work, break
down social and ethnic barriers, and encourage more involvement in public
service.
Sir Gordon Borrie, chairman of the commission, said: 'Almost 1m young adults
between the ages of 16 and 24 are not in employment, nor are they training,
nor studying.
'The costs of social exclusion for this group are all too obvious. Citizens'
Service could give them and every other young adult a new stake in society.
It would combine volunteer commitments with meeting community needs.'
Labour is likely to strongly back such a scheme at the next election.
The commission's scheme is echoed by a cost-benefit analysis from the Henley
Centre, the independent forecasting organisation, which is also published
today. It says that introducing voluntary service for young people could
save Pounds 13.5bn over five years through a resultant fall in crime, and
Pounds 298m by reducing long-term unemployment.
The Henley Centre report, commissioned by the Community Service Volunteers
charity, envisages a voluntary work scheme costing Pounds 300m with 250,000
places each year for people aged 18 to 21. It would pay them Pounds 20 a
week plus a lunch allowance.
The report adds that the estimates of savings are 'very conservative'.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour chairman, yesterday said: 'There are 1m young
people not in work, training or further education. We need to offer them
some real hope.'
Henley Centre report. CSV, 237 Pentonville Road, London N1 9NJ. Pounds 2.95.
Commission report. IPPR, 30-32 Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA. Pounds
2.95.
</TEXT>
