<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Work scheme 'would cut crime'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Most of the cost of a national 'citizens' service' community scheme for
young people would be offset by a reduction in crime and an increase in the
employability of young people, according to two reports published today.
A cost-benefit analysis by the Henley Centre, the independent forecasting
organisation, says Pounds 13.5bn could be saved over five years through less
crime and Pounds 298m by reducing long-term unemployment.
The Henley Centre report, written for the Community Service Volunteers lobby
group, envisages a voluntary work scheme costing Pounds 300m with 250,000
places each year for people aged 18 to 21. It would pay Pounds 20 a week
plus a lunch allowance.
Meanwhile, Labour's Commission for Social Justice yesterday backed a
citizens' service scheme lasting three months for up to 150,000 young
people. The cost, says a commission report, would be Pounds 2,000 per person
including a Pounds 50 weekly allowance.
Such a scheme should not become a public works programme, or be a means of
substituting for paid labour, but would bridge the gap between education and
work, break down social and ethnic barriers, and encourage more involvement
in public service.
Labour is likely to strongly back such a scheme at the next election.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour chairman, yesterday said: 'There are 1m young
people not in work, training or further education. We need to offer them
some real hope.'
