<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Extra help for war widows urged
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alf Morris, Labour MP and parliamentary adviser to the Royal British
Legion, yesterday wrote to Mr John Major, the prime minister, urging him to
mark the 50th anniversary of D-day next week by giving widows of men killed
in the Second World War a Pounds 2,000 one-off payment.
He pointed out that last year's budget of Pounds 1.2bn for war pensions was
to be cut to Pounds 1.1bn. 'The total of 51,300 war widows in 1992, the
latest year for which figures are available, must mean that today there will
be no more than 50,000 still alive. I am not asking you to increase
expenditure, but simply to maintain it.'
</TEXT>
