<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Begging split blows Labour off-course
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour's European election campaign was blown off-course yesterday by
differences among shadow ministers about the party's response to
Conservative attacks on begging.
Claims by Mr John Major, the prime minister, that begging is unnecessary and
offensive have been widely condemned by opposition and Church leaders.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, said yesterday that Mr Major had
worsened the problem of poverty by withdrawing benefits from those aged 16
and 17 as a minister in 1988.
But Mr Brown refused to commit Labour to providing funds to reintroduce
teenage benefits. He said that the problem could be solved 'within existing
budgets'.
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, said teenagers needed
more support. 'If more money is required then that will have to be
considered,' he said.
Ms Joan Lestor, shadow minister for the family, said that there would be
less homelessness if 'the benefits to the young, in particular, equalled the
benefits in most of Europe'.
Conservative ministers were quick to exploit the differences of emphasis
between Labour's treasury and social security teams.
Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the treasury, wrote to Mr Brown
demanding details of Labour's plans for financing a resumption of teenage
benefits.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said it was clear that Labour 'would
not find more facilities beyond what we have done ourselves'.
Labour's disarray will hearten Conservative strategists, who believe that
the first week of their campaign was far from the disaster predicted by many
commentators.
Conservative divisions on Europe have been minimised by Labour's split on
begging, and the Liberal Democrats' divisions on the national veto in the
council of ministers.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, told Conservatives in Aberdeen: 'The
campaign has been going well for us.'
</TEXT>
