<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / LDP ex-official jailed over bribes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's opposition Liberal Democratic party suffered a fresh blow yesterday
when Mr Fumio Abe, a former senior LDP official, received a three-year jail
term for taking bribes.
The downfall of 71-year-old Mr Abe, once a close associate of former prime
minister Kiichi Miyazawa, comes at a time when a demoralised LDP is trying
to disassociate itself from its corrupt past and attract public support for
a return to government. This follows the arrest in March of Mr Kishiro
Nakamura, a former LDP construction minister, on charges of receiving
bribes.
Mr Abe's jailing is the latest in a recent resurgence of political
corruption scandals, a factor in the instability of Japanese government and
near paralysis in policy making.
Mr Abe, who is to appeal against the Tokyo district court ruling, was found
guilty of taking Y630m (Pounds 4m) from Kyowa, a now defunct steel frame
maker and property company. In return, Mr Abe helped Kyowa get construction
jobs in Hokkaido, where he was head of the local development agency.
The Kyowa scandal was one in a chain of events that led to last June's
collapse of the Miyazawa government.
Mr Morihiro Hosokawa - Mr Miyazawa's immediate successor - resigned last
month after just eight months in office because of alleged financial
impropriety.
</TEXT>
