<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Andean Pact nations in tariff accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The five countries of the Andean Pact have agreed to a common external
tariff, 25 years after the formation of the group. Officials agreed in Lima
last week that a four-tier external tariff should come into force at the
start of next year, with some exceptions.
Venezuela, Colombia and Ecuador agreed to a four-tier external tariff
structure of 5, 10, 15 and 20 per cent. For Colombia, according to Trade
Minister Juan Manuel Santos, the weighted average tariff will be 11 per
cent.
Ecuador has negotiated a list of 600 exceptions for which it can, for a
four-year period, set a tariff of 5 per cent either side of that agreed for
other countries.
As the least developed country in the group, Bolivia will stick at its
current two-tier tariff level of 5 and 10 per cent.
Peru will accept the 5 and 10 per cent tariff, but its acceptance of other
tariff levels is still not settled and will depend, for example, on
concessions from Colombia over its free trade zone.
'We have come further in two years of negotiations that in the previous 23,'
Mr Santos said in an interview. He said the reasons for the success were the
involvement of the private sector in the negotiations, and the concept of
'open integration', meaning the group remained open to trade with the
outside world.
He said Colombia was moving ahead with other free trade negotiations. The
Group of Three accord with Venezuela and Mexico should be signed in mid-June
at an Ibero-American heads of state meeting in Cartagena.
Negotiations with the Caribbean Community resume on June 5 with a view to a
free trade deal, and he expected an accord with the Central American Common
Market before the government of Mr Cesar Gaviria quits in August.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>VEZ  Venezuela, South America.
    COZ  Colombia, South America.
    ECZ  Ecuador, South America.
    BOZ  Bolivia, South America.
    PEZ  Peru, South America.
</CN>
