<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Pace quickens in rebuilding of Beirut / A look at the
immensity of the task and progress so far
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than three years after the end of Lebanon's devastating civil war,
there are few visible signs of reconstruction and recovery. Parts of central
Beirut have street lighting. Electricity supplies are less erratic. Schools
are being rebuilt. Opulent shopping malls and marbled apartment buildings
are rising in Beirut's more select areas.
But for the planners of Lebanon's redevelopment programme, the big heave is
only now getting under way. The government of Mr Rafik Hariri, the
billionaire contractor who became prime minister in 1992, has set itself the
target of re-establishing Lebanon as an 'upper middle income country' by the
year 2000, and of restoring its role as a regional commercial, financial and
services hub to capitalise on a prospective Middle East peace.
The government estimates this will need public investment of Dollars 11.7bn
(Pounds 7.75bn) over the next decade and total private investment of twice
that. Lebanon, with gross domestic product of around Dollars 5bn, must
therefore simultaneously raise these immense amounts and the confidence
among local and international investors that will be needed if the project
is to succeed. 'It is a Herculean task,' says one Lebanese banker. But work
is in progress.
The Council for Development and Reconstruction, the state agency contracting
out the bulk of Lebanon's infrastructural work, is advertising for 50 new
professionals - planners, economists, lawyers, engineers - to join its 150
staff because, says Mr Boutros Labaki, CDR's vice president, 'the rhythm of
reconstruction is going to accelerate'.
Solidere, the Dollars 1.8bn company created by the government in a flotation
this year to develop downtown Beirut, meanwhile, is set to double its staff
to around 160 in the next two months, by which time preparatory works will
have begun on Lebanon's crown jewel project to revive Beirut's commercial
core.
Mr Nasr Chamaa, Solidere's managing director, says the Dollars 560m turnkey
project to repair central Beirut's basic infrastructure, a four-year task,
should be awarded by mid-July and work begun by August. Twenty two companies
have already bid for the project.
CDR has awarded 380 contracts worth Dollars 625m in the power, water,
transport, telecommunications, water, housing, education and other sectors.
The biggest so far, a Dollars 422m deal for refurbishing and expanding
Lebanon's telephone lines was awarded earlier this year to Siemens, Ericsson
and Alcatel.
A flush of other big deals is imminent. The cabinet last week, for instance,
is understood to have approved a Dollars 300m deal with France Telecom and
Finnish Telecom to establish a 500,000-line cellphone network. Letters of
intent have been agreed with Hochtief, the German construction group, and
local partners Consolidated Contractors Company, for the Dollars 400m
rebuilding of Beirut international airport.
Within the next couple of months, CDR is expected to announce the winner of
a Dollars 720m tender to build two 450MW combined cycle power plants. There
will also be a Dollars 400m project to revive the coastal railway, and a
Dollars 126m refurbishment of Beirut port.
CDR calculates its investment requirements over the next five years at
Dollars 7bn, after which officials say Lebanon's infrastructure will be
rebuilt and expanded.
The sheer scale of the project raises the question of how it is to be
financed, not least while the government pursues tight economic policies
which aim to reduce domestic and foreign debt from a predicted peak of 84
per cent of GDP next year (it was 50 per cent in 1992) to 39 per cent by
2002.
So far the government has won international loans and grants, mostly from
Arab and other international agencies, for Dollars 1.6bn - 23 per cent of
its proposed investment spending over the next five years. It is discussing
further lending and aid with Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the World Bank, and with
France on the financing of the two power plants.
No one in government underestimates the task of raising the billions of
dollars still required, particularly in the face of competing regional
demands, most notably in Gaza and Jericho.
Part of the solution, according to Mr Labaki, will lie in varying the
financing of projects on an almost case-by-case basis. The cellphone deal,
and a proposed Dollars 60m Beirut-Syria motorway will, for example, be on a
Build-Owner-Transfer basis. Bidders for the power plants are required to
provide their own financing for the deal. Mr Labaki says the government
plans to issue, for the first time, dollar-denominated treasury bills in a
Dollars 300m sale to finance housing and road-building in Beirut's suburbs.
But the effort is considerable and it will prove feasible, in the view of
local economists, only if the government can tempt back more of the billions
of dollars of expatriated Lebanese wealth it began to tap with the Solidere
flotation. This raised Dollars 650m through the sale to Arab investors of
Dollars 100 shares, a secondary market in which will open next month.
No one knows the scale of such overseas wealth, held by the often wealthy
Lebanese communities in West Africa, North and Latin America. Mr Freddie
Baz, economist for Banque Audi, a local commercial bank, estimates that
resident Lebanese alone hold Dollars 8bn in overseas deposits. He says new
instruments such as the proposed dollar T-Bills could raise up to Dollars
500m a year from those Lebanese investors shy of taking a risk on the
Lebanese pound.
Some other Lebanese - and Gulf - investors are nevertheless happy to take
that risk, and the flow of money into currently high-interest local currency
T-Bills has contributed to Lebanon enjoying its first balance of payments
surplus in the first quarter since 1988.
But economic growth is currently a more modest 4 per cent, and Mr Baz
describes productive investment flows as 'stagnant and timid'. Lebanese, and
international investors, happy perhaps to make short-term plays on local
T-Bills, generally want to 'wait and see'.
The dilemma for Mr Hariri's government is that while investors may prefer to
bide their time, the fate of his project for the country demands otherwise.
CDR and Solidere, which resemble as much as anything sophisticated marketing
machines, must prove within the next few years, that their and Mr Hariri's
hard-sell self-belief is infectious.
