<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / European Elections: Ireland's domestic issues dominate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Olive Braiden, a Fianna Fail candidate for the four-seat Dublin
constituency, sums up the general level of interest in Europe among
Ireland's 2.6m voters. Sipping a bowl of hot potato soup in a cafe in a
south Dublin shopping centre, after passing a bitterly cold morning shaking
hands and chatting with shoppers, she says, 'I am absolutely appalled at how
little people know about European affairs'.
Most of the 54 candidates contesting the 15 Irish seats are discovering that
domestic issues such as taxation and unemployment are of more concern to the
electorate than European affairs. At the Dublin bookmakers, Ireland's
performance in next month's World Cup is attracting considerably more
attention than the odds on Ireland's Euro-candidates.
This indifference comes in spite of the large amounts of EU funding flowing
to Ireland. The country's diplomats in Brussels are so effective in lobbying
for funds that one EU official gives them the collective appellation
'Ireland Inc'.
Up to the end of the decade, Ireland is due to receive IPounds 6.2bn (Pounds
6.08bn) in EU structural and cohesion funds from the EU, about 9 per cent of
total payments. Per head of the population this is significantly more than
will be obtained by Greece and Portugal.
Most Irish people derive their favourable view of Europe from the image of
Brussels as a cash cow to be milked thoroughly and regularly. In the
referendum on Maastricht in June 1992 the electorate voted by a majority of
more than two to one in favour of the treaty on European union.
Nevertheless, according to a random poll conducted by one of the Labour
candidates a fortnight ago, only 2 per cent of constituents can name their
local sitting MEPs.
On the Dublin campaign trail, Ms Braiden has been canvassing for the past 11
weeks, assisted by an enthusiastic crowd of friends and relatives. They have
already seen Ms Braiden's brother-in-law, Mr Ray MacSharry, successfully
climb the Euro-ladder, first as an MEP and then as the Commissioner for
agriculture in Brussels.
Reflecting how constituents are mainly concerned by national issues, Ms
Braiden says, 'It depends on what part of Dublin you are in. Here in the
wealthier southside, people are concerned about property tax. On the
northside, where unemployment can be as high as 75 per cent in some
neighbourhoods, people just want to know what is going to be done about
jobs.'
For the European elections, Ireland is divided into four constituencies.
Three of them - Dublin, Leinster, Munster - have four seats each.
Connacht-Ulster has three. As in the country's general elections, a single
transferable vote system is used.
The Fianna Fail party of prime minister Albert Reynolds has six outgoing
MEPs. Its junior partner in the coalition government, Labour, has just one.
Labour in particular, will be hard-pressed to repeat its performance of the
1992 general elections when it more than doubled its share of the vote from
9.5 per cent to over 20 per cent.
Judging from recent opinion polls, Fianna Fail is likely to emerge with five
to seven seats, Labour with none to two and the opposition Fine Gael and the
Progressive Democrats (PDs) with four or five and one respectively.
</TEXT>
<XX>
