<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Economic Watch: German engineering orders rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Orders for Germany's engineering sector in April rose 3 per cent in real
terms compared to April 1993, the VDMA, the engineering industry
association, reported yesterday. The increase in orders, which appear to
confirm that the industry is now emerging from recession, was boosted by a
particularly strong growth in exports to European Union countries. They rose
21 per cent over the same period, increased by 15 per cent during February
and April of this year when compared to the same period last year, and rose
by 8 per cent between February and April this year. However, domestic demand
remains sluggish. The VDMA reported a fall of one per cent between April
1993 and 1994. Judy Dempsey, Berlin
Italian employment in major industrial companies with over 500 workers fell
5 per cent in February 1994 from the corresponding month of 1993 and was
unchanged from January, the state statistical office Istat said yesterday.
The decline was evident in all sectors. Among the worst hit areas were
textile and clothing jobs (down 8.2 per cent) and chemical and related
sectors (down 8.3 per cent).
Belgium's year-on-year inflation was a preliminary 2.56 per cent in May, up
from 2.41 per cent in April but down from 2.69 per cent a year earlier, the
Belgian government said yesterday.
Sweden's current account showed a surplus of SKr2.7bn in the first quarter
of this year according to new calculation methods, the Central Bank said in
a statement.
</TEXT>
