FT  31 MAY 94 / Telecoms report presented
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Martin Bangemann, industry commissioner, yesterday told telecoms
ministers that the liberalisation of telecommunications networks across
Europe could be achieved without large injections of public sector finance.
Presenting findings of the long-awaited industry report on the future of
Europe's telecoms markets, he said discrepancies between member states in
areas such as data protection and the remaining constraints on public sector
telecoms companies acted as more of a hindrance than scarcity of funding.
Ministers decided to press ahead with preparations for arrival of digital
television, agreeing to step up research and pave the way for harmonious
development across the continent by adopting joint standards. But the tricky
question of conditional access - ensuring only viewers who pay for
programmes get them - remained unsettled. No decision will be made until
September.
