<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Plans to restructure Alitalia, loss-making state-owned national carrier,
will be scrutinised for the first time by the new Berlusconi government at a
meeting between the airline's chief executives and Mr Publio Fiori, the
transport minister. Within the Berlusconi government there are strong
pressures for cuts and changes even more radical than those proposed by the
three month-old board of Alitalia.
Several ministers want to use Alitalia as a demonstration of the
government's resolve to pursue free market policies and extend the scope of
the previous Ciampi administration's privatisation plans. Alitalia has
accumulated losses of L1,229bn (Pounds 513.3m) over the past six years, and
almost a quarter of that during 1993. The restructuring plan, which has been
presented to representatives of air and ground staff over the past two
weeks, has yet to be made public. But the unions fear the restructuring
proposed would involve cuts of over a fifth of the workforce.
