<TEXT>
A series of opinion polls yesterday showed Chancellor Helmut Kohl pulling
ahead of Mr Rudolf Scharping, his challenger in the October elections,
helped by an improving economy and stronger support in eastern Germany. The
respected Allensbacher monthly poll showed one in five Germans still
questioning the government's leadership ability, compared with one in three
at the beginning of the year. In eastern Germany the doubters fell from 22
per cent to 15 per cent over the same period.
One of four polls published yesterday showed Mr Kohl's Christian Democratic
Union (CDU) leading by 42 per cent over 39 per cent for the opposition
Social Democratic party (SPD). Three other polls showed the CDU leading with
smaller margins while the Allensbacher monthly poll showed the SPD ahead but
falling from 40.6 per cent to 36.3 per cent in April alone.
