<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Greeks wrestle with the ins and out of banking: Turbulence
in financial markets has led to some unorthodox limits on withdrawal of
funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Just before closing time in a crowded National Bank of Greece branch in
central Athens, the cashier shouted: 'Will anybody with a deposit to make
please come to the head of the queue.' Two people in a line of 30 customers
walked forward, each clutching a single cheque. Conserving funds at a time
of financial turmoil, the bank was willing to give priority service for any
customer willing to make a deposit.
The call for depositors at National's branch in Skoufa Street has echoed in
banks across Athens as turbulence in Greece's financial markets moved beyond
dealing rooms and into the streets.
Bank customers complained that withdrawal slips had suddenly disappeared
from local branches.
They also said some 24-hour automated teller machines had been unplugged by
midnight - just the hour that Greeks planning a plate-smashing session at a
bouzouki club are looking for extra cash.
The unorthodox limits on withdrawals have come in the wake of moves by the
socialist government, to avert a devaluation of the drachma. It has lifted
short-term interest rates as high as 500 per cent and, with overnight
inter-bank borrowing rates averaging more than 200 per cent last week,
branch managers were determined to conserve funds.
Following the lifting of capital controls this month, Greek businessmen can
now take abroad as much foreign currency as they want, but there are now few
dollars or D-Marks to be found in Athens. One clothing trader complained:
'On Friday, it took a trip around seven banks in the centre of town to
collect DM1,500.'
The National Bank, the largest commercial bank, which has about 35 per cent
of total deposits in Greek banks, should be immune from pressure. However,
it told some customers last week that they would withdraw no more than 50
per cent on money deposited last week.
It also refused to open new corporate accounts and was charging interest
rates at an annual rate of 150 per cent on one-week loans, which are
generally used by small businesses to cover payroll costs at the end of the
month.
However, the banks complain that some company treasurers were quick to
exploit the surge in short-term money market rates by raising additional
loans and exploiting interest rate differences. These were used to buy repos
 -fixed-term repurchase agreements - from other banks, at interest rates
ranging from 55 to 90 per cent.
'This week we've been looking very carefully at loan requests, even from our
best customers,' said one banker.
Consumer lending, on the rise since the socialists tried in February to
inject some life into the economy by raising the ceiling on consumer credit
to Dr8m (Pounds 21,500), has collapsed as a result of the surge in interest
rates.
Greece's smaller private banks, generally run by shipowners or insurance
companies, specialise in devising imaginative loan products, and are
suffering under the weight of interest rates.
'What looked like a promising market has died,' said a car dealer, whose
hire-purchase network is linked with a bank's consumer lending programme.
'There's no way anyone can risk offering an instalment agreement in this
climate.'
The rise in short-term interest rates will be reflected in government
borrowing from this week. New issues will include a one-month zero-coupon
bond at 27 per cent, restricted to investors who can put up a minimum of
Dr15m and a three-month treasury bill at 25.5 per cent, up from 16.5 per
cent last month.
While the new bond issues should attract large cash inflows for financing
the public sector deficit, the cost to the government will include further
losses in VAT revenues as companies postpone payments. VAT revenue is
running at only 3 per cent above last year against a budget target of 22 per
cent. 'Companies are preparing to postpone their VAT payments in order to
take advantage of high interest rates for repos and treasury bills,' said
one analyst.
High rates are also the socialists' main weapon in the battle to prevent a
flight of capital, now that the last capital restrictions have been removed.
However, the lifting of restrictions has been accompanied by a web of
bureaucratic regulations likely to make transfers abroad will be complicated
and time-consuming.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GRZ  Greece, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
    P6029 Commercial Banks, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>ECON  Inflation.
    ECON  Economic Indicators.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
