<PROFILE>_AN-EE4DFAAOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Germany aims to privatise military support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany has followed Britain in starting a drive to rationalise and where
possible privatise support services for its armed forces.
The German proposals on procurement and possible privatisation of logistics
and maintenance operations, launched quietly this month by Mr Volker Ruhe,
defence minister, could reduce the nominal price of Eurofighter 2000, the
controversial military aircraft.
While not as radical as Britain's Front Line First project, a cost saving
drive whose details will be announced by July, the German exercise includes
ideas familiar to defence planners in London.
Both countries' armed forces are now expected to move to a new system of
procuring spare parts that will operate more like the civilian motor
industry, using a reduced number of large depots supplying components in
response to computerised orders. Up to now, spare part depots serving allied
forces in Germany have been small, numerous and scattered to avoid
vulnerability to attack. This factor is now felt to be less important.
The German plan, to be overseen by Mr Jorg Schonbohm, calls for the possible
privatisation of weapons maintenance and some military training. It also
envisages wider use of the British practice of market testing, in which
private companies and internal divisions of the armed forces are invited to
compete for engineering or maintenance contracts.
But in some fields the plan could require increases in short-term
expenditure as a prelude to longer term savings. It calls for upgrading of
logistics and transport systems, seen as necessary when German defence
policy is placing greater stress on creation of rapid reaction forces.
Introduction of ISDN communications systems is also to be speeded up in the
belief that the corresponding increase in efficiency will pay for the
innovation in a few years.
The initiative follows submission in March to the German defence ministry of
a set of recommendations prepared by General Lorenz Huber with the help of a
management consultancy firm.
Although the plan makes no reference to Eurofighter, it appears to provide
at least part of the explanation for reports suggesting the unit cost of the
aircraft will be slashed as a result of privatisation of logistics and
maintenance.
Stern magazine has suggested that the aircraft's price tag of DM125m (Pounds
50m) per unit includes a DM68m logistics component which could be slashed by
up to 30 per cent if the work were farmed out to the private sector as
opposed to in-house engineers.
A spokesman for Deutsch Aerospace, the German manufacturer of Eurofighter,
confirmed that the company had put it to the government that privatising
logistics and maintenance could lead to substantial savings.
Germany has provisionally said it will buy 140 of the aircraft, starting in
2002, but no final decision will be taken till next year.
The defence ministry is currently engaged in delicate negotiations with
Deutsche Aerospace over funding of the development phase. Completion of the
development phase by the four partner countries - others are Britain, Spain
and Italy - will be seriously complicated unless the dispute is resolved in
the next few weeks, before the German parliament goes into summer recess.
</TEXT>
