<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Airbus ministers get tough with US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The four nations which make up the Airbus consortium yesterday urged the
European Commission to 'act vigorously' in talks with the US on an
international trade regime for civil aviation.
European irritation has grown over alleged interference in the aviation
market by the White House and the US Commerce Department, which are
perceived to have leaned heavily on foreign governments to buy US aircraft.
Trade and economy ministers from Britain, Germany, France and Spain were
meeting in the margins of the Berlin Air Show to discuss the issue.
Mr Gunter Rexrodt, the German economy minister, said he and his colleagues
had decided to write to the Commission urging it to maintain a firm stance.
Negotiators from the European Union and the US started work a month ago on
renewing a trade pact sealed in July 1992 which covers civil aviation but is
regarded by the Europeans as unsatisfactory.
Another European complaint is that the US government is heavily subsidising
US aviation through the back door by funding research which is nominally
connected with defence but has beneficial side effects for the civil sector.
Mr Rexrodt said: 'There are indications that the Americans are proceeding in
a very unconventional way.'
