<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Oil predicted 'to remain' at around Dollars 12-Dollars 15 a
barrel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The widespread perception that oil prices are 'low' may be incorrect,
according to a new study which suggests that prices in the Dollars
12-Dollars 15 a barrel range in 1993 money are the long-term norm. Current
prices for the benchmark Brent Blend are hovering around the Dollars 16 a
barrel level.
The report by London brokers Societe Generale Strauss Turnball finds no
evidence to suggest that there will be any long-term shortfall in oil. The
'inherent tendency (is) for oil supplies always to exceed demand,
irrespective of the rate of growth in oil consumption,' it says.
Mr John Toalster, oil analyst and one of the report's authors, said oil
supply, rather than demand, was the primary influence on prices. 'This
pre-eminence is likely to become even more marked in future,' he said.
The study dismisses current fears that a capital shortage among
financially-strapped members of the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting
Countries could lead to long-term supply shortages later this decade, when
demand is expected to rise strongly as areas such as Europe and Japan move
out of recession.
Mr Toalster concedes that there could be a temporary 'mismatch' between
supply and demand which could push prices up. But he contends that over the
longer term there is 'always a tendency for prices to fall.'
The report is optimistic that non-Opec output, widely expected to fall in
coming years, could be maintained through cost-cutting and the application
of new technology. This could further dampen price pressures.
The report suggests that trade wars could arise between Opec countries,
non-Opec producers and the oil producing countries of the former Soviet
Union vying for market share. It also suggests that fuel competition between
oil and natural gas is likely to intensify.
The historical record shows that oil production has been profitable even at
low price levels. The 'wealth, power and prestige' which flows from control
of oil reserves ensures the 'rapid and relentless' growth in reserves, a
process that is accelerated by advances in technology.
</TEXT>
