FT  31 MAY 94 / Fashion chief questioned on insider trading claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Pierre Berge, chairman of Yves-Saint-Laurent, the famous French fashion
house, and a close friend of President Francois Mitterrand, yesterday was
questioned by a Paris court over allegations of insider dealing in
Saint-Laurent's shares.
The questioning follows a legal coup for Saint-Laurent earlier this month
when it won FFr2m (Pounds 230,000) in damages by successfully suing Ralph
Lauren, a leading New York fashion designer, for copying one of its designs.
However, the same court slapped a FFr500,000 fine on Mr Berge for making
defamatory remarks about Ralph Lauren in the US press.
Yesterday's case was the latest instalment in an investigation into
suspected insider trading in Yves Saint-Laurent's shares during the summer
of 1992.
