<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Paris resists timetable on liberalisation: Row over air
routes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French government yesterday confirmed that it would open Orly airport to
UK airlines flying from London from June 13, but said it would resist the
timetable demanded by the European Commission for the liberalisation of some
domestic routes.
Mr Bernard Bosson, transport minister said that Orly airport, in southern
Paris, would be opened to British carriers with a limit of four daily return
flights per airline. From the summer of 1995, the routes will be limited to
aircraft with more than 200 seats during the morning and evening peak travel
periods.
However, it was necessary to implement competition on a gradual basis, he
said. France would appeal to the European court of Justice concerning an
order by the European Commission to open the Orly-Toulouse and Orly
Marseille routes by the end of the autumn.
Britain welcomed the opening of Orly airport to London flights, but
expressed concerns about the limits placed on the frequency of services.
British Airways, which must share its allocation of four daily flights with
TAT European Airlines, its French affiliate, said it would challenge the
restrictions.
Yesterday's announcement follows a compromise agreement between France and
Britain which was reached two weeks ago and which averted a damaging
showdown between British airlines and the French government.
Mr Bosson said that the opening of the London-Orly route was in line with
French policy and would allow cheaper air travel.
The French government also stressed that French carriers must receive
improved access to London's Heathrow airport as part of the compromise
agreement with the British government. Air Liberte, a small French airline,
however, said that the problem of access to Heathrow had not been resolved.
</TEXT>
