<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Tapie: man of the moment in France
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The assembled Eurosceptics at a recent Paris rally of Sir James Goldsmith's
L'Autre Europe movement greeted the video images of the conservative and
socialist party leaders with mild derision. But when the permanently tanned
face of Mr Bernard Tapie appeared, the crowd went wild with jeers, boos and
hisses.
Love him or loathe him - and it is hard to find anyone in France who admits
to being indifferent to him - Mr Tapie, 51, the leader of the left-wing
Energie Radicale movement, is the man of the moment in the French campaign
for the European elections.
Thanks to his leadership Energie Radicale, once a motley assortment of
activists with little more than 2 per cent of the votes, now scores 10 per
cent in the opinion polls. Mr Tapie himself has raced ahead of the other
left-wing contenders to claim third place in the polls for next year's
presidential elections. He fares even better among young voters by tying for
first place alongside Mr Edouard Balladur, the centre-right prime minister.
His success is all the more surprising in the light of his financial and
legal problems. Mr Tapie, who was born in a poor Paris suburb but made a
fortune in the 1980s by buying bankrupt companies, has sold off his business
empire leaving a bitter legacy of heavy debts and court cases.
Olympique-Marseille, the football club that he groomed into the first-ever
French winner of the European Cup, is reeling from a recent match-rigging
scandal and faces relegation to the second division. Mr Tapie is currently
embroiled in no fewer than six judicial investigations.
Credit Lyonnais, his bank, is so concerned about his financial situation
that it has given him until Thursday to repay FFr450m (Pounds 52.4m) of his
FFr1.2bn debts. If Mr Tapie fails to pay, Credit Lyonnais will seize the
contents of his Paris home. It recently sent a bailif to take an inventory
of the contents of his Paris town house only to discover that its own
private detectives had previously filmed the removal of some of the most
valuable objects. The prospective Euro MP said he had lent a few 'favourite
pieces' to his mother-in-law.
His legal and financial plight is so dire that Mr Tapie's critics claim the
only reason he is standing in the European elections is the hope that yet
another layer of parliamentary immunity might help keep him out of prison.
Yet his personal problems seem only to have enhanced his standing among his
supporters and to have helped, rather than hindered, his progress in opinion
polls.
'The public sees Bernard Tapie as an adventurer, as part of modern French
folklore,' says Serge Raffy, a political commentator on Nouvel Observateur,
the current affairs magazine. 'To them he's one of the few people who dares
to wave two fingers at the establishment. Every time Credit Lyonnais, the
legal system or the tax authorities gang up against him, it just adds to the
Tapie myth.'
Mr Tapie has always styled himself as a man of the people. He is known for
his love of fast cars, big boats, flashy clothes and for devotion to his
football club. Whereas most French politicians pride themselves on peppering
their speeches with obscure literary or historical references, he is
notorious for livening up television chat shows by threatening to throttle
his opponents.
His image has made him an anathema to the Paris political establishment. Mr
Franz-Olivier Giesbert, editor of the conservative Le Figaro, recently
described Mr Tapie as the 'prince of swagger' and 'a loud-mouthed
guttersnipe'.
But the same earthy style has made him one of the few public figures that
ordinary people can relate to in a country where the upper ranks of finance,
industry and politics are filled with the haut bourgeois products of the
snooty Grandes Ecoles. Besides some people actually like Mr Tapie. He
recently topped a poll as the man most French women wanted to go to bed
with.
Mr Tapie's street chic has proved invaluable during his current crises. Each
time that Credit Lyonnais has stepped up the pressure over the past few
weeks, he has been swift to style himself as the victim of an establishment
plot. His conspiracy theories have struck a chord with the public.
A poll in last Sunday's Journal du Dimanche newspaper showed that nearly a
third of the electorate think he is being hounded by the establishment.
Yet even Mr Tapie seems to be finding it difficult to wriggle out of Credit
Lyonnais's clutches. He often claimed in past crises that all he really
wanted was to sail away on the Phocea, his luxury yacht. But the Phocea is
now the subject of a tax probe and is also threatened with seizure by Credit
Lyonnais as security for Mr Tapie's outstanding loans.
</TEXT>
