<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Banks back China power project: Dollars 120m loan paves the
way for further private-sector finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
China yesterday signed a Dollars 120m (Pounds 80m) loan agreement with a
consortium of international banks for the co-financing with the World Bank
of a Dollars 1.3bn power project in Jiangsu province, west of Shanghai.
It was China's first co-financing deal involving private institutions under
the World Bank's Expanded Co-Financing Operations Programme, and is expected
to become a model for other such arrangements. The deal paves the way for
increased commercial lending to China's infrastructure development
programme.
In the power sector alone, it is estimated that China will require Dollars
10bn-Dollars 12bn a year for the next few years to fund its requirements in
the light of anticipated economic growth of 9 per cent-10 per cent a year to
the end of this decade.
The World Bank is lending Dollars 350m to the project, which will entail
building two 600-megawatt coal-fired generators in Yangzhou city, about
100km north-east of Nanjing, Jiangsu's capital.
JP Morgan of the US, Bank of Tokyo, and Dresdner Bank of Germany are
arranging a Dollars 90m syndicated loan, while Nippon Life Insurance of
Japan will provide a yen facility worth Dollars 30m.
Morgan executives said the loan, in which China's finance ministry
represented the People's Republic, appealed to China because of the long
maturities and the fact that the interest rate was some 40-60 basis points
below market rates.
The Dollars 120m loan carries a 15-year final maturity and a five-year grace
period. Repayments of principal after the 10th year are guaranteed by the
World Bank. The bank's involvement encouraged the commercial banks to lend,
whereas, in the past, many have been wary of repayment difficulties in
infrastructure projects.
Debt financing for the Yangzhou plant is an alternative to Build Operate
Transfer arrangements for the power sector.
Beijing is currently embroiled in a dispute with financiers over what might
be considered adequate returns for such a financing arrangement for a power
project.
The World Bank has made clear that it favours greater private-sector
involvement in the funding of infrastructure projects. Mr Ernest Stern, the
bank's managing director, has said that such participation could 'bring
additional benefits that go beyond finance, including management expertise
and new technology.'
Funding for the Yangzhou power station, one of China's largest energy
projects, will also come from the State Energy Investment Corporation, local
Jiangsu institutions, and the Yangzhou Municipality. Other banks involved in
the syndicated loan include the Korea Development Bank, the Long-Term Credit
Bank of Japan and Mitsubishi Bank.
</TEXT>
<XX>
