<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For bank holiday Monday the people who run television have contrived one of
the most unattractive schedules imaginable. Between 7.30 and 12.50 BBC2 are
showing nothing but programmes about the most boring game on earth; the
'sport' which gave us the professional foul, mouth-to-mouth all male
celebration, and Heysel. If you are one of those inverted snobs who love to
stand on the terraces supping lager wi' t'lads and chanting racist slogans
then presumably you will want to see the whole of Goal TV. Those with a
modicum of intelligence will want to look elsewhere - but where? Radio
appears to be the answer. Between 1.00 pm and 7.00 Radio 1 broadcasts
Listeners' Top 100 Songs, a poll of all-time favourites with the Top 10 at
6.00. The Monday Play on Radio 4 is The Triumph Of The Cunning Man by JR
Jones (7.45). Set in 1945 on the coast of Pembrokeshire, it is about Gwyn's
mission to recall his father and brothers who were killed in the war. That
is followed at 9.00 by Risking Your Neck, an investigation of the true risks
of, say, getting cancer from nuclear power or from x-rays.
</TEXT>
