<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Police call for anti-drugs campaign
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was facing growing pressure yesterday to launch an education
campaign to counter the increasing use of drugs.
But as police chiefs renewed their call for attention to be switched from
supply to demand for drugs, there was a claim of a cabinet split over plans
for a school-based initiative warning of the risks of addiction.
Whitehall moved swiftly to deny any rift between Mr Michael Howard, the home
secretary, and the education secretary Mr John Patten after a report in The
Mail on Sunday said Mr Patten believed that giving pupils hard-hitting
lessons about the dangers of hard and soft drugs could be
counter-productive.
A joint statement issued by both departments dismissed the report as
'ridiculous and without foundation'.
The denial came as Mr Keith Hellawell, the chief constable of West Yorkshire
and chairman of the chief constables' committee on drugs, stepped up
pressure for government action against the growing demand for drugs.
He told The Sunday Times: 'We've won several battles, but we've lost the
war. The current policy has not stopped young people turning to drugs.'
Mr Hellawell has suggested that cannabis might be legalised at some point as
part of a new approach to drugs.
