<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Labour's 1992 campaign 'lost before it was begun'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A powerful challenge to the conventional wisdom that Labour lost the 1992
general election as a result of a last-minute revolt by the electorate
against the party's tax policies has been made by a group of leading
academics.
In the most comprehensive analysis yet produced of the factors which gave
the Conservatives their fourth consecutive election victory, the study casts
serious doubts on the validity of opinion polls taken in the election
campaign.
The analysis concludes instead that Labour had in effect lost the battle
before the election campaign started, and that tactics employed by the main
parties immediately prior to the election had little impact on the outcome.
Turning to Labour's future electoral prospects, the team of academics says
that Labour does not need to be defensive about its tax policies and should
stick firmly to its commitment to preserve and improve the welfare state.
Instead it should focus on its policies for managing the economy. The key to
Labour's success must be to persuade 'a sceptical electorate that it has the
economic as well as the social formula to succeed in office'. The
Conservatives' reputation for economic competence has been seriously eroded
since 1992 but it is not clear how permanent the damage is.
The authors question the traditional judgment that a strong performance by
the Liberal Democrats would damage Labour's chances of forming a government.
Instead a high third party vote would allow Labour to win an overall
majority with no more than 35 per cent of its 1992 vote.
But it warns that an electoral pact would not help Labour because too high a
proportion of Liberal Democrat voters prefer the Conservatives to Labour.
The study was produced by the Centre for Research into Elections and Social
Trends and edited by a team of election specialists including Mr Anthony
Heath, Mr Roger Jowell and Mr John Curtice.
It says the root cause of Labour's electoral failure has been a sharp fall
over the past 20 years in the number of voters who instinctively identify
with the party. In 1970 they constituted 42 per cent of the electorate. In
1992 the proportion was 34 per cent.
The main cause of the erosion was Labour's lurch to the left and the split
with the SDP in the early 1980s. By contrast the proportion of the
electorate which identifies itself as Conservative remained remarkably
constant at 42 per cent.
Basing its conclusions on detailed interviews with a carefully weighted
sample of voters both before and after the 1992 election, the study says
that the Conservatives started the campaign at least six points ahead of
Labour.
Any late swing was therefore much too small to make any significant
difference to the outcome. The study also explodes the myth that the Tory
tabloid newspapers won the election for Mr John Major. Conservative support
among readers of the Tory tabloids fell three points during the election
campaign while it rose one point among readers of the Labour-supporting
Daily Mirror.
Labour's Last Chance? The 1992 Election and Beyond, edited by Anthony Heath,
Roger Jowell and John Curtice with Bridget Taylor, Dartmouth Publishing
Company. Pounds 47.95 hardback, Pounds 17.95 softback.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
