<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Conservatives win few points in opening round
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first week of full campaigning has brought no comfort to the
Conservatives. Every poll and every further analysis of its implications
must have lowered any hope of a respectable performance for the government.
The nationwide polls show no response to the better economic news. The
simple 'How will you vote?' questions reveal no trend.
But the bad news for the Conservatives lies in two factors concealed in
these simple nationwide figures.
The swing has been different in different regions: the Conservatives have
slumped most in the south and 28 of the 32 Euro-seats now held by the
Conservatives are below the line from the Severn to the Wash. One MORI
calculation shows the polls pointing to Labour winning 66 seats, leaving the
Tories with 15 and the Liberal Democrats with three. However, when regional
variation in swing is allowed for, the figures change to Labour taking 69
seats and the Conservatives only six - behind the Liberal Democrats' nine.
Even in the residual six Conservative seats, some seem too near the margin
for there to be any certainty about the outcome.
The Guardian interpretation of its poll is no less depressing for the
Conservatives. Allowing for regional variations, Mr John Curtice of
Strathclyde University suggests that the Conservatives will take only six
seats of the 83 shared by the three main parties, to Labour's 65 and the
Liberal Democrats' 12.
Neither of these polls makes much allowance for turnout, which could be
about 40 per cent. A great deal, therefore, depends on who gets to the
polling booths on June 9. Moreover, neither poll takes into account the
impact of last-minute tactical voting.
The local elections showed that an increasing number of Labour voters are
ready to switch to the Liberal Democrats if that will defeat the Tories. A
smaller number of Liberal Democrats will vote Labour where it makes sense
locally.
Polls have, of course, not been confined to voting intentions. They show
that the public, while not nearly as fearful as arch-sceptic Tories Mr
William Cash and Lord Tebbit would have us to believe, still rejects
overwhelmingly the idea of a federal Europe, and more narrowly opposes a
common currency.
The Conservatives naturally are playing on these fears but there is no sign
that they are winning further votes. The main reason is that European issues
are so low in popular importance compared with full employment, law and
order and the health service.
For poll-watchers the most innovative surveys this week involved the Labour
leadership. MORI and ICM have both found Mr Tony Blair well ahead among both
the general public and among those who vote Labour.
But, much more importantly, an ICM telephone survey among levy-paying trade
unionists with votes in the leadership race showed that their preferences
were much the same as those of the rest of the population.
Since inquiries among MPs and constituency activists - admittedly more
dubious as sample surveys - yield very similar findings, a Blair victory for
the leadership looks almost as certain as a Labour victory for Strasbourg.
But perhaps the most interesting poll of the week was the most amateur.
A survey carried out on behalf of a local newspaper in Eastleigh, Hampshire
 -where the by-election takes place simultaneously with the Euro-vote -
found the Liberal Democrats leading Labour by two to one, with the
Conservatives in third place - in a seat which they won with a majority of
17,000 at the 1992 general election.
David Butler is a fellow of Nuffield College, Oxford.
