<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Ashdown sets out sovereignty stance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, yesterday said he did not
believe in the sovereignty of parliament.
He said the Liberal Democrat party was the only one willing to let the
British people decide their future in the European Union and he offered a
referendum in the event of a further shift of power from Britain to Brussels
at the 1996 inter-governmental conference.
Mr Ashdown said in an interview with GMTV: 'There is this great theory that
sovereignty lies in parliament. I do not believe in the sovereignty of
parliament. I never have. I believe in the sovereignty of the people.'
He said he would have wanted a referendum on a single European currency but
the decision had already been taken that this should be decided by a future
parliament. 'But if (the single currency) were to come I cannot see any
circumstances it would be in British interests to be outside it,' he added.
Mr Ashdown said the Liberal Democrats could well recommend a change in the
balance of power between Westminster and Brussels because 'it gives us more
security and better cost-effectiveness for money spent on defence'.
Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, said: 'Paddy Ashdown keeps letting
the rat out of the bag - and the British people should take note.
'The Liberals are wholly committed to a centralised European superstate.
Only the Conservatives stand for a strong Britain at the heart of a strong
and diverse Europe.'
</TEXT>
