<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Call for merger of all Co-op retailers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A call for Co-operative retailers to merge into a single national
organisation, which would be one of the UK's largest retailers with annual
turnover of Pounds 7bn, was made at the Co-operative Congress.
Speaking in the 150th year of the co-operative movement and in its
birthplace - Rochdale - Mr Hughie Todner, congress president, backed calls
for co-operative societies to join forces.
He said the 41 remaining societies should come together in a new
Co-operative Consumer Partnership. The Co-op's financial institutions, the
Co-operative Insurance Society and the Co-operative Bank, should also merge.
'The combined resources and enterprise of these organisations could forge
new horizons in co-operation which could reach new heights of excellence,'
he said.
His call is likely to increase the pressure on the movement's two largest
retailers, Co-operative Retail Services and the Co-operative Wholesale
Society, which are in merger negotiations. A merger would form a group with
annual sales of Pounds 3bn, making it the UK's seventh-largest retailer. The
last attempt to merge the two groups failed in 1990 when they could not
agree on the composition of the board. But both groups are hopeful of
success this time.
Analysts say a merger is the only way for co-operative retailers to compete
effectively in a mature grocery market increasingly dominated by large
quoted companies such as J Sainsbury and Tesco.
The CWS has absorbed a number of smaller regional societies in recent years,
and has formed a buying and distribution partnership - the Co-operative
Retail Trading Group - with several others.
Mr Todner said that a national partnership would create greater financial
rewards for members and staff but it was important to safeguard the
movement's system of democratic control.
