<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Managers volunteer surplus expertise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British managers in the caring '90s like nothing more after a hard day at
work than to start managing again, it seems - but this time for no pay and
to help others.
The image of do-gooding managers has emerged from a survey published today
of 3,000 members of the Institute of Management.
More than half of the 857 managers who replied to the survey say they
undertake some form of voluntary work in the community. Two-thirds of those
who do not carry out community work say they would like to.
The main constraint cited is lack of time, particularly among younger
managers. The typical volunteer, says the report, is a male senior manager
in his fifties.
Their motives appear pure as well. Only one in 10 managers surveyed admits
that he or she is seeking to make social or business contacts. Most say they
volunteer from a sense of social responsibility and a feeling of
satisfaction from helping others.
One in four of the managers who do voluntary work is helping a charity.
Other activities include serving as school and college governors and as
trustees of charities, housing associations and health bodies, and
involvement with youth groups and heritage societies.
A quarter spend more than six hours a week on voluntary work and 80 per cent
receive no payment.
Mr Roger Young, the institute's director-general, said: 'This report shows
there is such a thing as a caring society after all.
'Britain's managers clearly do care about their communities and are prepared
to help by giving freely of their time and skills.'
He suggested that employers could allow managers more time to undertake such
work.
The expansion of the voluntary sector, including the creation of Training
and Enterprise Councils, housing action trusts and grant-maintained schools,
is creating increasing demand for good managers.
The survey says there is untapped potential among younger managers, many of
whom support the principle of giving their time and skills free of charge.
The report, published jointly with the Local Government Management Board -
the employers' body - says there is a need for some kind of brokering
service to match managers with voluntary opportunities.
Giving Something Back. IM Books, Burston Distribution Services, Unit 2a,
Newbridge Trading Estate, Whitby Road, Bristol, BS4 4AX. Pounds 41.
</TEXT>
