<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Court reforms could cut costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cost of going to court and the time taken to deal with civil cases in
England and Wales could be cut sharply by wide-ranging reforms being
considered under a government review.
The Lord Chancellor's Department said yesterday that Lord Justice Woolf, who
is heading the inquiry, has proposed that civil actions should be made
simpler, cost ceilings imposed, and control of civil cases taken from
lawyers so that people can represent themselves more easily.
He has also backed firm timetables for cases to be heard.
The radical changes would allow potential litigants to know in advance what
chances of success their actions would have, what they would cost, and how
long they were likely to last.
The changes were 'long overdue', said Mr Gareth Williams, former chairman of
the Bar. The legal process had shifted from being 'servant to master',
because of 'cost, length and uncertainty'.
Lord Woolf was put in charge of the review by Lord Mackay of Clashfern, the
Lord Chancellor. His report is expected in about two years, but proposals
could be put into effect quickly since in most cases they would not require
changes to the law.
Under Lord Woolf's proposals, if the courts were put in control of the civil
system legal aid could be given to more people as the cost of each case
would be cheaper. Courts would decide which legal route each case would take
and which timetable would apply.
New 'procedural judges' could take charge of High Court and County Court
cases at an early stage. Important and complicated cases would be handled by
these courts; others would be settled by arbitration where possible.
Most cases could be settled in a year under the reforms. One way to save
time would be to cut down on the volume of documents disclosed before
trials.
</TEXT>
