<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Call to merge co-operative retailers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Co-operative retailers should merge into a single national organisation,
which would be one of the UK's largest retailers with annual turnover of
Pounds 7bn, the Co-operative Congress was told.
Speaking in the 150th year and in the birthplace of the co-operative
movement - Rochdale, greater Manchester - Mr Hughie Todner, president of the
congress, backed calls for co-operative societies to join forces.
He said the 41 remaining societies should come together in a new
Co-operative Consumer Partnership. The Co-op's financial institutions, the
Co-operative Insurance Society and the Co-operative Bank, should also merge.
'The combined resources and enterprise of these organisations could forge
new horizons in co-operation which could reach new heights of excellence,'
he said.
His call is likely to increase the pressure on the movement's two largest
retailers, Co-operative Retail Services and the Co-operative Wholesale
Society, which are in negotiations after the CRS launched a new proposal for
a merger of the two earlier this month.
That would form a group with annual sales of Pounds 3bn, making it the UK's
seventh-largest retailer, and is seen as a first step towards a single
co-operative organisation.
The latest of three attempts to merge the two groups failed in 1990 when
they could not agree on the composition of the board. But both groups are
hopeful of success this time, and changes in their structure in the past
four years could make agreement easier.
Analysts say a merger is the only way for co-operative retailers to compete
effectively in a mature grocery market increasingly dominated by large
quoted companies such as J Sainsbury and Tesco.
The CWS has absorbed a number of smaller regional societies in recent years,
and has formed a buying and distribution partnership - the Co-operative
Retail Trading Group - with several others.
Mr Todner told the congress that a national partnership would create greater
financial rewards for members and staff, but it was important to safeguard
the movement's system of democratic control.
'A Co-operative Consumer Partnership must ensure that the ordinary
rank-and-file members are given an opportunity of playing a positive role in
the success of their society, and where accountability is in the controlling
hands of its local members,' he said.
</TEXT>
