<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Former communists win power in Hungary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Former communists returned to power in Hungary yesterday after winning an
absolute majority in the second and decisive round of parliamentary
elections.
The Hungarian Socialist party - the revamped communists - won 209 of the 386
seats in the new parliament. That enables the party to govern alone, if it
chooses, without the moderating influence of the coalition partner that the
diplomatic and business community had hoped for.
Hungary joins Poland and other east European countries where hardship has
pushed voters back into the embrace of revamped communists.
In yesterday's vote, the Socialists relegated the Hungarian Democratic
Forum, at present the largest party in the parliament, to a humiliating
third place with an estimated 37 seats, down from 165 in 1990.
The Socialists said earlier they would invite the Alliance of Free
Democrats, the liberals placed second with a 70 seats, to join a coalition
government.
However, the Free Democrats have said that an absolute Socialist majority
would all but preclude their participation in a coalition government in
which they would be dispensable. Nor, liberal leaders said, would they take
ministerial positions under Mr Gyula Horn, the 61-year-old Socialist leader,
a former foreign minister and long-time communist.
One-party government carries connotations of the monopoly of power exercised
by the communist regime and few even in the Socialist party favour the
option.
Mr Laszlo Bekesi, the Socialists' free-marketeer economic spokesman and a
possible compromise prime minister, said last week that only a broad and
solid coalition could implement the austerity programme necessary to contain
twin current account and budget deficits.
</TEXT>
