<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 94 / Further German rate cuts forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
German interest rates should continue to fall 'for many months to come' in
spite of the recent strong growth in German money supply, a new study from
Lehman Brothers, the US investment bank, argues today.
After a week in which Mr Hans Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank president, added to
the gloom in financial markets by damping expectations of step-by-step cuts
in German interest rates, economists from Lehman Brothers' London office
said that 'in the near term' they 'expect continued reductions in German
interest rates'.
Although M3, the broad measure of money supply, grew at an annualised rate
of 15.8 per cent in April, well outside the Bundesbank's 4 to 6 per cent
target growth range, the Lehman Brothers paper argued that Germany's credit
boom 'is over'.
Lehman's team of international economists is headed by Mr Gerry Holtham,
formerly a senior economist at the Organisation for Economic Co-operation
and Development in Paris.
They said Mr Tietmeyer had been right to claim that M3 has been swollen by
exceptional factors. Outside the property sector, where lending has been
boosted by changes in the tax treatment of mortgage interest payments, the
annualised growth of lending has slowed sharply to about 5 per cent.
Lehman Brothers said the Bundesbank should only worry 'in the unlikely event
that M3 does not decelerate in the coming three to six months'. Only if
broad money continued to grow by 15 per cent until the year-end, should the
Bundesbank react and raise interest rates, because that would be a sign that
bank credit was growing quickly.
Late last week, Mr Tietmeyer clarified his bearish comments by explaining
that he had been referring only to the Bundesbank's official discount and
Lombard rates and not to the 'repo' rate which it steers in its money market
operations.
Some economists still expect official German rates to fall further. Mr
Ulrich Ramm, chief economist of Commerzbank, one of Germany's big banks,
said the Bundesbank was likely to lower its discount rate by a further half
percentage point to 4 per cent by the end of 1994.
Writing in Borsen-Zeitung, a Frankfurt financial daily, Mr Ramm forecast
that the Bundesbank would 'continue its policy of cautious interest rate
cuts' until some time in 1995.
Commerzbank sees signs of solid full-year results, Page 17
</TEXT>
